[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

 {Hello everyone, my name is Robert Ris, an International Master from Amsterdam, the Netherlands. I am a professional chess trainer and content creator. I have my own YouTube channel, and I'm thrilled to present my first Lifetime Repertoire for Chessable.  This course revolves around the move1.e4for White, and our strategy will be to counter it with the move1...d5!} 1. e4 {White moves the king's pawn two squares in order to gain more control over the centre and enable the light-squared bishop to be developed soon. This move is by far the most popular continuation at any level and I'm sure it will always remain like that!} 
1. d5 {Welcome to the Scandinavian Opening a.k.a the Center Counter. Black opens the game by moving its queen's pawn two squares forward, immediately challenging its counterpart on e4 and thus not allowing White to occupy the centre with both its central pawns next to each other. Another advantage is that the light-squared bishop from c8 can be brought into play anytime (most likely either to f5 or g4), but that can still be decided at a later stage.} 
2. exd5 {Frankly, there is no more logical move than just taking the pawn and not surprisingly it has been considered as the only critical test for Black. Still, that doesn't mean the other options shouldn't been taken seriously. In Chapter 16 all the relevant sidelines are examined in detail to avoid any unpleasant surprises.} 
2. Qxd5 {Here we go! Already by move 2(!) we violate one of the main opening principles of bringing the queen out too early, before developing its own colleagues.   It's well-known that with such an approach you may either enjoy very quick successes or face early disappointments, depending on someone's own and opponent's skills. Still, why would Black choose such an early queen sortie and what are the benefits?    As said, the queen is very actively placed on d5 already (looking in all different directions) and even though it likely will become a target for any of White's minor pieces or pawns in the near future, it also offers Black tactical opportunities for us. With optimal play from White's side we may not be able to prove so, but once you recognize a strange move by your opponent make sure you are looking for tactical opportunities, including checks, captures and threats (double attacks, skewers etc.). Even many strong players, including top GMs have fallen victim of such tactical mishaps in the opening.    By trading off these two central pawns it means that the game gets a very open character with active piece play for both sides. I'm pretty sure that most people will enjoy this type of play more than what you get to see in a more closed type of games with subtle maneuvering.   The general plans and concepts are easier to comprehend for beginners and grandmasters alike. Still, from time to time I'd elaborate on more sophisticated positional topics like pawn structures, which pieces to trade or not, how to evaluate specific endgames, but the focus will be particularly on the dynamics the open centre has to offer us.    Concretely: as mentioned already the bishop from c8 can be developed very fast and will likely contribute to exerting pressure on White's position. The black queen on d5 covers so many squares depriving White's pieces from going there. The knights are usually being developed in the direction of the centre (apart from some exceptions, of course). Thanks to the exchange of pawns there are two half-open files in the centre, which generates new possibilities for both sides. Our goal is to neutralize White's potential pressure on the e-file, while we are contemplating plans of exerting pressure down the d-file (most likely against White's pawn on d4) either by ...Rd8 or even castling queenside in certain lines.    Good news for you, guys! By choosing the Scandinavian you avoid a lot of opening theory one has to know in other openings like the Sicilian, French, Caro-Kann and also 1.e4 e5. The amount of theory is one thing (Yes, there are much less sidelines one has to study!), but another aspect that attracts me and a lot of other people playing this opening is that after the exchange of pawns e4-d5 the pawn structure has basically been defined already. True, every position is unique and I didn't say it will be easy at all (otherwise chess would be too boring!), but the total package of opening lines will be easier to master than (almost) all the other openings against 1.e4.    Last but not least, there is a very big chance that you will surprise your opponent and isn't it great to gain a psychological advantage by putting your opponent with their back against the wall from the very first move!? Imagine you are building up an opening repertoire as White based on 1.e4. Most likely you will concentrate first on the 'main' openings like the ones mentioned above. From my own experience, I can say that the Scandinavian has done an incredible job of letting my opponents start thinking before I had to do so! On top of that, even if you are facing a very-well prepared opponent (we are not impressed anyway, as the positions we will get are ALL sound and playable for Black anyway!) what is the chance he or she will remember every single detail over-the-board?} 
3. Nc3 {Developing the knight with a gain of time, as Black will be forced to move Her Majesty again.} 
3. Qa5 {From all the possible squares the queen could go to, I believe this is certainly the most ambitious one. The main alternatives3...Qd6and3...Qd8are playable too, but with the text Black plays actively as long as possible, aiming to thwart White's development and launch a counterpunch (alone or with the aid of other pieces) whenever given the chance! Some concrete points: by sliding away from the centre to the side of the board, the queen can't be immediately harassed by one of White's minor pieces.The queen is in a great spot on a5 from where it retains control over the entire 5th rank and keeps an eye on the knight on c3  (after White touches its d-pawn, the knight will be pinned and therefore unable to move). Once the queen gets in trouble it usually drops back somewhere on the a5-d8 diagonal.} 
