1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Nf3 {The most logical move in terms of development has been the primary choice for White for quite some time. The knight is strategically positioned on f3, providing support to the pawn on d4. Meanwhile, others would opt to play it with the aim of swiftly building up pressure with Ne5.} 
5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Bc4
6. e6 {Neutralizing the potential pressure against the f7-pawn and preparing to get the bishop out to b4.} 
7. Bd2 {With the idea of setting up a discovered attack on the queen with Nd5, but our next move was already on the agenda.} 
7. Bb4
8. Nh4 {Aiming to win the pair of bishops, but the knight surrenders the protection of the d-pawn.} 
8. Nc6 {This has never been tried, but it certainly makes sense. Just after:} 
9. Nxf5
9. Qxf5
10. Bd3
10. Qg4 {Attacking both pawns on d4 and g2 and thus forcing the exchange of queens.} 
11. Qxg4
11. Nxg4 {Black has the more pleasant game as d4 is a long-term target.} 
12. a3 {It's important to realize there is no need to trade the bishop for the knight.} 
12. Ba5 {Maintaining the pressure and possibly dropping back to b6.} 
13. f3
13. Nf6
14. Ne2 {Simplifying, but White's problems are not over yet.} 
14. Bxd2+
15. Kxd2
15. O-O-O
16. Ke3 {Stepping out of the d-file, but now:} 
16. e5 {This still offers Black a small initiative as ...Rhe8 is coming next.} 
