7. Qb6
8. Be3 {After having played so many pawn moves, covering the central dark squares with this bishop move seems to me as the natural follow-up.8.Bc4e6before generating counterplay by means of ...a7-a5, I'd rather complete my kingside development with9.Nge2Be710.O-OO-Oand a perfectly playable position for Black, similar to the lines arising 5.Bd2. Perhaps White is a tad better, as the engines are appreciating extra space. However, such a space advantage also comes with more responsibility and frankly, I believe that Black has very decent chances here. Two possible plans:   1) Either to counter soon with ... a7-a5 and meet b5-b4 with ...a5-a4 to create a square for the queen on a5. Soon ...c7-c6 may be considered.   2) ...a7-a6 with the idea of initiating the exchange of our light-squared bishop on b5 to create a bit more space for our remaining pieces.} 
8. e6 {Let's keep it simple, there is no need for an immediate ...a7-a5 yet.} 
9. Qd2 {Protecting the bishop on e3, as in certain lines the break d4-d5 becomes possible.9.Bc4,apparently the mixture of White's moves is already imprecise.9...a5!pressurizing the pawn on b4.10.b5c6!White can't play Rb1 as that would drop the pawn on a3, while after11.bxc6Qxc6the vulnerability of White's unprotected pieces on the c-file is felt. Still, the position is more or less equal, but easier to play for Black.} 
9. Be7 {Simply continuing our development, as10.d5?!isn't problematic on account of10...c5!} 
10. Bc4
10. a5 {Trying to take advantage of White's ambitious pawn play in the opening as we are looking for counterplay.} 
11. b5
11. a4 {An important resource. Black vacates the a5-square for the queen in case it comes under threat after d4-d5. Black is about to castle, place the rook on d8 and attempt to create some play in the centre with ...c7-c6.} 
