[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Bc4 {The second most popular move (after5.Nf3) is a very logical one. The bishop is nicely placed on c4 from where it attacks the pawn on f7 and takes away some valuable light squares from the black pieces. Note that often play may transpose to lines starting with5.Bd2.} 
5. Bg4 {Like in the line with 5.Bd2 I think this provocative move makes quite a lot of sense and it fits best with our repertoire.} 
6. Nge2 {The most natural alternative to 6.f3.White retains the possibility of chasing the bishop with f2-f3 after which the knight can decide to harass the bishop either from f4 or g3, depending on where the bishop goes.} 
6. e6 {The most sensible continuation, basically abandoning the idea of pressurizing the d-pawn with our standard plan of ...Nc6 and castling queenside, as often we would like to get our pawn to e5 in one go.} 
7. O-O {The most popular move, but not one we have to fear. Since White has castled it's very unlikely Black is going to expand on the kingside by pushing the pawns. On the other hand, White is hinting at the idea of playing f2-f3, Ng3 and push the f-pawn further to f5.} 
7. Nbd7 {In most games Black has opted for7...c6, but developing a minor piece first is better.} 
8. f3 {The only critical attempt in my view. After other moves, Black will put a pawn on c6 so the queen is always able to retreat to c7 and set up a battery with the dark-squared bishop on the b8-h2 diagonal.} 
8. Bf5
9. Ng3
9. Bg6
10. f4 {White has tried various other moves, but in general, I think Black's position is easy to play. The text seems threatening and is consistent with the previous moves, as by getting in f4-f5 White attempts to remove Black's pawn from e6 when the bishop on c4 gains in power.However, now it's time to reveal the point of starting with7...Nbd7(instead of7...c6) .} 
10. O-O-O {Our king is safe at the other side of the board and there is no longer a constructive plan for White. Some clear drawbacks having pawns on d4 and f4:   1) White's dark-squared bishop becomes pretty useless.   2) White's king becomes more vulnerable along the a7-g1 diagonal.} 
11. f5 {This has no longer the desirable effect and can strongly be countered.} 
11. Ne5 {Attacking the bishop and taking advantage of the pin along the d-file.} 
12. fxg6
12. Rxd4 {The rook can't be taken by13.Qxd4in view of13...Bc5!} 
13. Bd3 {White tries to save the piece.} 
13. hxg6 {Black has at least two pawns for the piece, but even more important is that all of the pieces are ready to strike. Among Black's ideas are:   1) Doubling of rooks on the h-file, targeting the pawn on h2.   2) Setting up threats via the g1-a7 diagonal either with the queen or bishop.   3) A knight coming via g4.} 
14. h3 {Relatively White's best option anticipating points 1 and 3.} 
14. Qb6 {With the idea of ...Rxd3.} 
15. Be3 {15.Kh1?sidestepping the discovered check backfires, in view of15...Qc6!with the threat of taking on h316.Kg1Bc5-+and White's position totally collapses.} 
15. Rxd3
16. Bxb6
16. Rxd1
17. Raxd1
17. axb6 {With two pawns for the exchange Black has excellent chances of winning the game.} 
