4. Qe2 {A rare move. White is intending to offer the exchange of queens on b5, but neglects their own development, since the queen obstructs the bishop on f1.} 
4. a6 {Other moves are sensible too, but why not annoy your opponent when given the chance!?} 
5. g3 {Since the queen is blocking off the f1-a6 diagonal for the light-squared bishop, fianchettoing the bishop seems to be the most logical continuation.5.Nf3Nc6!An excellent response. Black is intending to meet 6.g3, planning to fianchetto the light-squared bishop with 6...Bg4 and 7...Nd4.6.d4Leads to some sort of mainline in which White has opted for the weird-looking Qe2.6...Nf67.h3Planning to meet ...Bf5 with g2-g4.(7.g3?allows7...Bg4leads to immense problems for White, as the pawn on d4 can't be defended properly).7...Be6!?Black is going to castle next. White is already under pressure.} 
