3. Nf6 {Simply defending the pawn. By the way, this variation could also be reached via the 1.d4 move order, so if you were in doubt this course is just much more than a complete repertoire against 1.e4 :)} 
4. f3 {Welcome to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, a popular variation at club level.} 
4. exf3 {Let's once again accept the challenge by simply capturing the pawn!} 
5. Nxf3 {The most logical way recapturing on f3.} 
5. c6 {From all Black's options I like this one the best. It's a sort of useful waiting move to see how White is going to develop the light-squared bishop. And of course, it also actually fits well with structures normally arising from the Scandinavian.} 
6. Bc4 {This is by far White's most popular move, as it looks at the vulnerable f7-pawn and thereby creates several tactical ideas. However, with precise play Black is able to prove White's move to be inaccurate.} 
6. Bf5 {Next is ...e7-e6.} 
7. Ne5 {The most aggressive option.} 
7. e6
8. g4 {White hasn't castled yet, so the following resource should spring to mind!} 
8. Nfd7 {Opening the path for the black queen coming to h4.} 
9. gxf5
9. Qh4+
10. Kf1
10. Nxe5 {If White recaptures then the bishop on c4 will be taken.} 
11. Be2
11. Qh3+
12. Ke1
12. Be7 {No need to move the knight away, but instead mobilizing our pieces is the way to punishing White's overambitious play.} 
13. dxe5 {13.Bf4Ned714.fxe6Qxe6∓Black is a healthy pawn-up.} 
13. Qg2 {Very precise.} 
14. Rf1
14. Bh4+
15. Kd2
15. Na6 {Next comes a rook to the d-file. White is completely lost, as the bishop can't interfere on d3 because of the pin along the 2nd rank.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.e4 d5 2.e5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. e5 {This move has seldomly been seen at high level. By advancing the pawn on e5, White is grabbing space in the centre. However, in most lines we will see that it likely more becomes a weakness rather than an asset.} 
2. c5 {Black anticipates that White is going to support the pawn on e5 by creating a chain with c3-d4.} 
3. c3
3. Bf5 {The most precise continuation. Black would like to play ...e7-e6 but first the light-squared bishop needs to be activated before it gets stuck within its own pawn formation.} 
4. d4
4. e6 {Simple and strong. Black obtains a favorable version of the Advanced Variation of two popular openings.  1) French: after1.e4e62.d4d53.e5c54.c3Black's light-squared remains passive on c8. In our line, it's outside the pawn chain controlling various valuable squares.  2) Caro-Kann: after1.e4c62.d4d53.e5Bf5Black spends an extra tempo by playing twice with the c-pawn. Let's see how we can try to take advantage of this small plus!} 
5. Nf3 {The most common move, as the knight supports the chain by overprotecting the pawns on d4 and e5.} 
5. Nc6 {Dito: the knight puts pressure on White's pawns.} 
6. Bd3 {A typical move you would often seen at club level. Trading off these bishops seems to enlighten the pressure, but what matters is what remains on the board. The bishop on c1 is worse than their counterpart on f8.} 
6. Bxd3
7. Qxd3
7. Rc8 {Ready to open the c-file.} 
8. O-O
8. cxd4
9. cxd4
9. Nb4 {Attacking the queen and to trap the rook in the corner.} 
10. Qb5+
10. Qd7
11. Qxd7+
11. Kxd7 {The king is actually well placed on d7, supporting the rook on c8.} 
12. Nc3
12. Ne7 {This is not just a boring queenless middlegame. Black has an edge! Why?   Well, as mentioned black has the better bishop and White has to take care of the weak pawn on d4, the base of the chain, which could easily come under the attack of the black knights. Another important plan is challenging the head of the chain, White's pawn on e5, with ...f7-f6 when after ...exf6, ...gxf6 Black obtains a mobile pawn centre which eventually may turn into a passed pawn.} 
