16. Nd5 {With a stable advantage for Black. Our blockading knight on d5 is the hero of the board, as it puts pressure on the bishop on c3 and restricts their mobility. Additionally, the knight has the potential to move to e3 (with the possibility of a knight fork) or f4, presenting mating ideas against the white king. White struggles to activate their pieces, as the knight on d5 also covers the entry square e7. By the way, in such positions, we shouldn't hesitate to offer the exchange of queens with ...Qg6.   Ideally, Black would like to exchange the queens and one pair of rooks. By keeping one rook on the board, Black retains more opportunities to exploit potential weaknesses in conjunction with the knight.} 
