10. Nc6 {There are actually some subtle differences between the text and10...O-O, which was seen in the high-profile game Caruana-Mamedyarov, Zagreb 2019.In that game, Black proceeded to play solidly by developing the knight via d7. However, I think our choice of posting the knight on c6 does offer more practical chances to play for an advantage. The knight exerts pressure against the pawn on d4, while the rook could do the same by going to d8. In combination with ...Be4/Bg4, the d-pawn becomes seriously vulnerable. Note that White is rarely able in this line to break with d4-d5 as long as the queen is on d1, on account of O-O-O, pinning the d-pawn. A drawback of Black's last move is that the queen is temporarily short of squares, so please keep that in mind!   However, quite a number of strong players failed to come up with an instructive plan as White, so that gives me good hope you will enjoy playing this line as Black.} 
11. b4 {At first, this looks like an anti-positional move, but White is trying to take advantage of slightly misplaced pieces on the queenside.} 
11. O-O
12. b5 {Consistently played.} 
12. Nb8 {This has never been tried, but it is a good alternative.} 
13. Bb4
13. Rc8
14. Bc5
14. Qa5 {The queen is fine here.} 
15. Bb4 {There is no need to settle for a repetition.} 
15. Qa4 {Hitting the pawn on f2 and undermining the pawn on b5 by means of ...a7-a5.} 
