[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Nf3 {The most logical move in terms of development has been the primary choice for White for quite some time. The knight is strategically positioned on f3, providing support to the pawn on d4. Meanwhile, others would opt to play it with the aim of swiftly building up pressure with Ne5.} 
5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Bc4
6. e6 {Neutralizing the potential pressure against the f7-pawn and preparing to get the bishop out to b4.} 
7. Bd2 {With the idea of setting up a discovered attack on the queen with Nd5, but our next move was already on the agenda.} 
7. Bb4
8. a3 {8.O-ONc69.a3Bxc310.Bxc3Qb6transposes to this line.} 
8. Bxc3
9. Bxc3
9. Qb6
10. O-O
10. Nc6 {There are actually some subtle differences between the text and10...O-O, which was seen in the high-profile game Caruana-Mamedyarov, Zagreb 2019.In that game, Black proceeded to play solidly by developing the knight via d7. However, I think our choice of posting the knight on c6 does offer more practical chances to play for an advantage. The knight exerts pressure against the pawn on d4, while the rook could do the same by going to d8. In combination with ...Be4/Bg4, the d-pawn becomes seriously vulnerable. Note that White is rarely able in this line to break with d4-d5 as long as the queen is on d1, on account of O-O-O, pinning the d-pawn. A drawback of Black's last move is that the queen is temporarily short of squares, so please keep that in mind!   However, quite a number of strong players failed to come up with an instructive plan as White, so that gives me good hope you will enjoy playing this line as Black.} 
11. Re1
11. O-O-O
12. Qc1 {was seen in Kravtsiv-Tzermiadianos, Al Ain 2012, but now} 
12. Be4 {to intensify the pressure against the pawn on d4 is thematical.} 
13. Ne5 {Hoping Black is going to take on e5 when two minor pieces are hanging, but we are not falling for such cheapos.} 
13. Bg6 {An idea worth remembering! White still has to think about how to deal with the d4-pawn.} 
14. Nf3 {An invitation for a quick draw, which could kindly be declined.} 
14. Ne4 {With a fighting position in which I'd rather be on the Black side.} 
