8. a3 {8.O-ONc69.a3Bxc310.Bxc3Qb6transposes to this line.} 
8. Bxc3
9. Bxc3
9. Qb6
10. O-O
10. Nc6 {There are actually some subtle differences between the text and10...O-O, which was seen in the high-profile game Caruana-Mamedyarov, Zagreb 2019.In that game, Black proceeded to play solidly by developing the knight via d7. However, I think our choice of posting the knight on c6 does offer more practical chances to play for an advantage. The knight exerts pressure against the pawn on d4, while the rook could do the same by going to d8. In combination with ...Be4/Bg4, the d-pawn becomes seriously vulnerable. Note that White is rarely able in this line to break with d4-d5 as long as the queen is on d1, on account of O-O-O, pinning the d-pawn. A drawback of Black's last move is that the queen is temporarily short of squares, so please keep that in mind!   However, quite a number of strong players failed to come up with an instructive plan as White, so that gives me good hope you will enjoy playing this line as Black.} 
11. a4 {A direct attempt to catch the queen, but I think it's counterproductive.11.Ne5O-Otransposes to 10.Ne5.} 
11. a5 {Stopping White's plan and securing the b4-square for the knight.} 
12. Bb5
12. O-O {With the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 inserted, castling queenside is no longer attractive obviously.} 
13. Nd2 {White got to do something as otherwise Black will simply intensify the pressure against the pawn on d4. With the text White aims to bring the knight to c4, hitting both the queen and after the queen moves, followed by Bxc6 and the pawn on a5 is hanging.} 
13. Nb4 {Anticipating White's plan and setting up a threat against the pawn on c2.13...Nxd4?fails to14.Nc4!and White wins a piece.} 
14. Nc4
14. Qa7 {The queen may look strange on a7, but at least it's pretty safe and it still keeps an eye on the d-pawn. Black threatens to trap the bishop with ...c7-c6.} 
15. Ne3
15. Bg6 {This position has been reached in a few grandmaster games. The dark-squared bishop is awkwardly placed on c3, but good solution can't be found easily.} 
16. Bxb4
16. axb4
17. Qd2
17. Rfd8
18. Qxb4
18. Rxd4 {Thanks to the control over the d-file, Black is comfortable in Asgarizadeh-Papaioannou, Nakhchivan 2013.} 
