10. Nbd7 {Black ignores the tension and instead develops the remaining minor piece to avoid any Bxf6 ideas ruining Black's pawn structure. It should be said though that in various games Black has also played10...exd5, but I believe our choice is more pragmatic.} 
11. Qe2 {White is increasing the pressure on the pawn on e6, but Black a simple antidote. Note that the following line could also be reached if White starts with capturing on e6 instead of this queen move.} 
11. O-O
12. dxe6
12. Bxe6 {First, the annoying e6-pawn has to be removed, avoiding any unnecessary tactical ideas.} 
13. Bxe6
13. Rae8 {Very precise, as with13...Rfe8White has the additional option of playing14.Ng5, although that's fine for Black as well.} 
14. O-O
14. Rxe6 {Black is more active and therefore there is no need to go for the exchange of queens, though objectively speaking the position is very equal.} 
