13. O-O
13. Rhe8 {A first glance will probably make you think that White is better here thanks to the better pawn structure and bishop pair, but fortunately, perceptions can be deceptive. Particularly, White's light-squared bishop, hindered by the pawn on d5, doesn't look great at all.   Most importantly, I think in this case Black's major pieces are more active and thanks to the control over the e-file also the knights are able to impose new threats, as I would like to demonstrate with the following analysis.} 
14. Ba2 {This was seen in Alekseev-Mamedov Kocaeli 2014. White's idea to make sure the bishop will not come under attack anytime soon, but such a slow approach enables Black to become active.} 
14. Ne5 {All of Black's pieces are nicely placed and White also got to take care of the d-pawn.} 
15. Re1 {15.Qd4Nxd5!and Black wins a pawn.} 
15. Ne4
16. Bd4
16. c5 {Exploiting White can't take en passant.} 
17. Bxe5
17. Rxe5
18. Qc1 {Defending b2.18.f3runs into the discovered check18...c4+!with mate to follow.} 
18. Qf6 {With a dream position for Black. The rook is well protected and thus we don't have to reckon with f2-f3. The plan is to install the knight on d6, a wonderful blockading post from where it dominates White's light-squared bishop and the queenside majority.} 
