[White "2) 5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Bc4 - 8.a3 Main lines"]
[Black "8.a3 Bxc3 9.Bxc3 Qb6 10.d5 Nbd7 11.Nd4 #8"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Nf3 {The most logical move in terms of development has been the primary choice for White for quite some time. The knight is strategically positioned on f3, providing support to the pawn on d4. Meanwhile, others would opt to play it with the aim of swiftly building up pressure with Ne5.} 
5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Bc4
6. e6 {Neutralizing the potential pressure against the f7-pawn and preparing to get the bishop out to b4.} 
7. Bd2
7. Bb4
8. a3
8. Bxc3
9. Bxc3
9. Qb6
10. d5 {A concrete attempt to take advantage of the bishop pair and that Black's king is still in the centre. In his Lifetime Repertoire 1.e4 Part 1, Wesley So recommends this particular variation and wants to claim an edge for White, but let's not get intimidated by the analysis of a top GM! :)} 
10. Nbd7 {Black ignores the tension and instead develops the remaining minor piece to avoid any Bxf6 ideas ruining Black's pawn structure. It should be said though that in various games Black has also played10...exd5, but I believe our choice is more pragmatic.} 
11. Nd4 {A concrete idea trying to refute Black's opening play. White threatens either to take on f5 or e6, in both cases irreparably damaging Black's pawn structure.} 
11. O-O-O {It's essential Black castles in this direction now so that the king is safe and the queen's rook joins the action along the d-file once it gets opened.} 
12. Nxf5 {Black was planning to move away the bishop, so this move is pretty much forced.} 
12. exf5 {Black has the idea to play ...Rhe8, so White has no choice.} 
13. O-O
13. Rhe8 {A first glance will probably make you think that White is better here thanks to the better pawn structure and bishop pair, but fortunately, perceptions can be deceptive. Particularly, White's light-squared bishop, hindered by the pawn on d5, doesn't look great at all.   Most importantly, I think in this case Black's major pieces are more active and thanks to the control over the e-file also the knights are able to impose new threats, as I would like to demonstrate with the following analysis.} 
14. Re1
14. Rxe1+
15. Qxe1 {This was played in Dulany-Nucci, ICCF 2012, and here I would make a small improvement for Black:} 
15. Re8 {Just occupying the only open file.} 
16. Qf1 {Intending to let the rook come into play.} 
16. Ne4
17. Bxg7 {This is the only move, as the bishop doesn't have a convenient square.} 
17. f6 {Disconnecting the bishop.} 
18. Bb5
18. a6
19. Bxd7+
19. Kxd7 {The king is safe here.} 
20. b4
20. Qd4 {With the idea of ...Nxf2.} 
21. Rd1
21. Qe5
22. Bh6
22. Nc3
23. Rd3
23. f4 {With a rather unusual situation, but White's extra pawn is meaningless as Black is simply too active. In fact, the current position seems to be quite tricky for White due to the lack of coordination (stranded bishop, back rank etc.).} 
