[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Bd2 c6: 7.Ne4, 7.Nh4, and 7.Bc4"]
[Black "5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Bd2 c6 7.Ne4 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Nf3 {The most logical move in terms of development has been the primary choice for White for quite some time. The knight is strategically positioned on f3, providing support to the pawn on d4. Meanwhile, others would opt to play it with the aim of swiftly building up pressure with Ne5.} 
5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Bd2 {A tricky move order that presents serious challenges for Black. It is no longer advisable for Black to pursue the plan of ...e7-e6 and ...Bb4.Therefore, it is important to note that the moves6.Bd2and6.Bc4have differences and require separate approaches.} 
6. c6 {The reliable continuation, ensuring the queen can always drop back to either c7 or d8 once it comes under attack.6...e6?!has been played in many games and indeed transposes after7.Bc4to the lines covered in the chapter with 5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Bc4. However, this time7.Ne5!is quite annoying for Black as pointed out by Gajewski in his course.} 
7. Ne4
7. Qc7 {There is no need to go to d8 this time.} 
8. Nxf6+
8. exf6 {Capturing away from the centre has my preference so that the f8-bishop can be brought into play. This idea is actually known from a trendy line in the Caro-Kann (1.e4c62.d4d53.Nc3dxe44.Nxe4Nf65.Nxf6exf6).  For a long period of time these type of positions were considered favorable for White, but nowadays it's proven that Black has quite a lot of piece activity to compensate the doubled f-pawns. Compared with that particular line in the Caro-Kann I like the black bishop on f5, not enabling White to place their own bishop on d3.8...gxf6this recapture towards the centre is, of course, possible too and has been played by a lot of people who believe the asymmetrical pawn structure offers better practical chances to outplay the opponent.} 
9. Bc4
9. Bd6 {The most active square for the bishop, preparing to castle.} 
10. Qe2+ {10.O-OO-Oit's also possible to play these structures with queens on the board, but in general, I believe Black is very comfortable here. In certain cases, Black may even consider the pawn break ...c6-c5 to open the files for the major pieces.} 
10. Qe7
11. Qxe7+
11. Bxe7 {With a roughly equal position. As long as there are sufficient pieces on the board it's very unlikely White will be able to mobilize the 4 vs. 3 majority on the queenside. Black's ideas:   1) Possible opt for the trade of light-squared bishops with ...Be6, improving the pawn structure and gaining more control over the d5-square.   2) Gain some space on the queenside with ...a7-a5 (sometimes following it up with ...b7-b5 as well) and develop the knight either via a6 to c7 or d7 to b6.   3) Normally Black will castle kingside, but keeping the king in the centre (d7) also makes sense as queens have been traded.} 
