7. Nbd7 {More precise than7...e6as the discovered attack on the queen is no longer problematic, as we are able to recapture with the knight.} 
8. O-O {is the second most popular move, but after} 
8. e6 {we get a typical structure which has often been seen in other openings like the Caro-Kann for instance, but I think it's rather harmless because of the following reasons:   1) White has castled kingside too quickly, depriving him of sharp lines usually arising when castling on the other side.   2) The idea based on Nd5xf6 is no longer problematic, as Black is able to recapture with the knight.   3) There is no chance to break through in the centre with d4-d5.    I hear your question coming: 'But what is Black's plan?'   1) Very likely the queen will drop back to c7 where it can form a nice tandem with the bishop on the b8-h2 diagonal.   2) A solid approach based on castling kingside and centralize the pieces (... Rad8-Rfe8), pressurize the d-pawn and aim for simplifications is perfectly fine.   3) In a must-win situation Black could also consider castling queenside and launching a pawn storm on the kingside. In case White decided to go for an early Nh4xg6 trading off the bishop, the h-file is already open and offers Black new opportunities as well.} 
