3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Nf3 {The most logical move in terms of development has been the primary choice for White for quite some time. The knight is strategically positioned on f3, providing support to the pawn on d4. Meanwhile, others would opt to play it with the aim of swiftly building up pressure with Ne5.} 
5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Bd2 {A tricky move order that presents serious challenges for Black. It is no longer advisable for Black to pursue the plan of ...e7-e6 and ...Bb4.Therefore, it is important to note that the moves6.Bd2and6.Bc4have differences and require separate approaches.} 
6. c6 {The reliable continuation, ensuring the queen can always drop back to either c7 or d8 once it comes under attack.6...e6?!has been played in many games and indeed transposes after7.Bc4to the lines covered in the chapter with 5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Bc4. However, this time7.Ne5!is quite annoying for Black as pointed out by Gajewski in his course.} 
7. Bc4 {7.Ne5Nbd7!transposes to lines discussed after 6.Ne5.} 
7. Nbd7 {More precise than7...e6as the discovered attack on the queen is no longer problematic, as we are able to recapture with the knight.} 
8. Qe2 {The only ambitious attempt, planning to castle queenside. White threatens Nb5-d6.} 
8. Qc7 {8...e6?has been played by some very strong players, but does allow White to open the centre with9.d5!which should rather be avoided.} 
9. O-O-O
9. e6 {A simple move, which is going to be useful anyway as it controls the d5-square and releases the dark-squared bishop. White has a small lead in development and quite a number of possibilities.} 
10. Ne5 {White launches the knight and prepares to expand on the kingside with g2-g4 and f2-f4 which is potentially very dangerous.} 
10. h5 {The idea is pretty clear as it stops White's plan of pushing the g-pawn. This anti-developing move truly fascinates me, but if you aren't impressed wait for our next move!10...Nxe5?this is a tempting idea to aim for simplifications, but it's actually pretty bad.11.dxe5Nd512.g4!Bg613.f4O-O-O14.Rhf1!intending to push f4-f5 when Black is under severe pressure.} 
11. Nxd7 {11.f4?is a clear mistake, because of11...Nxe5!12.fxe5Bg4and Black wins the exchange.11.h3will be answered by11...h4!} 
11. Kxd7 {This move deserves a double exclamation mark, one because it's simply beautiful and the other one as it's objectively Black's best continuation.   The other recaptures are simply inferior as they can be met by the central thrust d4-d5. As long as the files remain closed, the black king is absolutely safe on d7. However, you shouldn't take matters too lightly now and the main thing on our priority list is to play ...Rad8 and ...Kc8.} 
12. f3 {12.d5?exd5!Intending ...Re8 and Be6 refutes the attempt to punish Black's provocative play.} 
12. Rd8
13. Ne4
13. Kc8 {Mission accomplished and as a bonus the pawn on d4 is under threat now too.} 
14. Bg5 {14.c3?fails to14...Nxe415.fxe4Bg4winning the exchange.} 
14. Be7 {And Black is doing absolutely fine in Thiel-Mueller, Germany 1997.} 
