[White "3) 5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Bd2 c6: 7.Ne4, 7.Nh4, and 7.Bc4"]
[Black "5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Bd2 c6 7.Bc4 #21"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Nf3 {The most logical move in terms of development has been the primary choice for White for quite some time. The knight is strategically positioned on f3, providing support to the pawn on d4. Meanwhile, others would opt to play it with the aim of swiftly building up pressure with Ne5.} 
5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Bd2 {A tricky move order that presents serious challenges for Black. It is no longer advisable for Black to pursue the plan of ...e7-e6 and ...Bb4.Therefore, it is important to note that the moves6.Bd2and6.Bc4have differences and require separate approaches.} 
6. c6 {The reliable continuation, ensuring the queen can always drop back to either c7 or d8 once it comes under attack.6...e6?!has been played in many games and indeed transposes after7.Bc4to the lines covered in the chapter with 5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Bc4. However, this time7.Ne5!is quite annoying for Black as pointed out by Gajewski in his course.} 
7. Bc4 {7.Ne5Nbd7!transposes to lines discussed after 6.Ne5.} 
7. Nbd7 {More precise than7...e6as the discovered attack on the queen is no longer problematic, as we are able to recapture with the knight.} 
8. Qe2 {The only ambitious attempt, planning to castle queenside. White threatens Nb5-d6.} 
8. Qc7 {8...e6?has been played by some very strong players, but does allow White to open the centre with9.d5!which should rather be avoided.} 
9. O-O-O
9. e6 {A simple move, which is going to be useful anyway as it controls the d5-square and releases the dark-squared bishop. White has a small lead in development and quite a number of possibilities.} 
10. Nh4 {The most critical continuation. White is trying to claim the pair of bishops.10.d5?simply doesn't work, because of10...cxd511.Nxd5Nxd512.Bxd5Qxc2#.} 
10. Bg6
11. Nxg6 {White has played various other moves in this particular position, but this trade has to be played sooner or later.} 
11. hxg6
12. h4 {White's most challenging option. White sets up an attack on the kingside, and the move h4-h5 becomes a significant possibility once the knight vacates f6.The move12.h3is the modest alternative to the main line with12.h4. In many games, Black opts to castle queenside, but in this position, I would lean towards a more proactive approach with12...b5!?, mirroring the main line.} 
12. b5 {An important novelty, in my opinion. Gajewski only mentioned castling queenside after which White has a clear risk-free advantage. My new idea is certainly more adventurous and even if it doesn't fully equalize, I believe it certainly offers Black reasonable practical chances. The main point is to increase the grip on the light squares and generate some counterplay on the queenside.Gajewski concludes his analysis with12...O-O-O13.Bb3±.} 
13. Bb3 {The best square for the bishop, as the bishop sacrifice on e6 still doesn't work for White. However, I doubt many people would dare to play this move as Black's a-pawn is running fast.} 
13. Nb6 {The main point of Black's setup. Before anything else, we got to make sure White can't break through in the centre with d4-d5.13...a5?is premature, because of14.d5!and Black is dead lost, as14...a4runs into15.dxe6!} 
14. g4
14. a5 {14...Bb4This developing move has been played before in one correspondence game, but the text is more aggressive and appeals more to me.} 
15. g5 {15.a3?!b4!gives Black a chance to open the files first.} 
15. b4 {An important counterpunch.15...Nfd5?isn't possible, because of16.Nxd5Nxd517.Bxd5cxd518.Qxb5+and White is a pawn up.} 
16. gxf6
16. bxc3
17. Bxc3
17. gxf6
18. h5
18. g5 {The position offers chances to both sides. Slow play would definitely help Black to consolidate the position and try to exploit the weakened pawn formation on the kingside in the long run.} 
19. d5 {Initiating a long sequence of mainly forcing moves.19.a4Nd520.Bd2Bb421.c3Be7=looks totally fine for Black.} 
19. a4
20. d6 {20.Bc4?fails to20...Qf4+!and Black wins a bishop.} 
20. Bxd6
21. Bxe6
21. O-O {21...Rh6!?is worth considering too. White doesn't have a good discovered check, so on the next move Black is happy to place the king on f8.} 
22. h6 {22.Bf5?!Nd523.Rxd5cxd524.Bxf6with the idea of mating with the h-pawn, but Black is in time.24...Bf4+25.Kb1Qd6!⩱26.Be7?is met by26...Rfe8!} 
22. Bf4+ {Important to give his check before taking the bishop on e6.} 
23. Kb1
23. fxe6
24. Qxe6+
24. Qf7
25. h7+
25. Kh8
26. Qxc6
26. Rab8 {Black has to defend the knight and searches for counterplay.} 
27. Rh6
27. Be5
28. Bxe5
28. fxe5 {Black is ready to take over with ...Rfc8 and ...Nc4.} 
29. Rg6 {Only move.} 
29. Nc4
30. Rg8+ {30.Rd7Na3+comes down to the same.} 
30. Rxg8
31. hxg8=Q+
31. Kxg8
32. Rd7
32. Na3+
33. Kc1
33. Qf4+
34. Kd1
