20. bxc4
21. fxg7 {21.dxe6gxf6is unproblematic for Black.} 
21. Bxg7
22. Bxb4
22. e5 {I think it's an appropriate moment to cut the line right now. White is a pawn-up and is objectively a bit better, but the endgame is very sharp. Black will put the king on d7, neutralizing White's passed pawn.   White's pawn on h4 is vulnerable and can be easily attacked by doubling rooks on the h-file and/or ...Bf6. On the other hand, Black's pawn on c4 is the weakest point and can be challenged by Re1-e4, but Black has ...Rc8 as an antidote.   I think White has a difficult time mobilizing the extra pawn on the queenside and frankly, I wouldn't be surprised to see things going wrong for White in a practical game. Or am I trying to sell my course too hard now?} 
