5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Ne5 {The most aggressive option for White with various ideas like either placing the knight on c4, bringing the queen to f3 or opt for a quick g2-g4. We have to be alert now!} 
6. c6 {The key move so that the black queen will never be trapped.6...e6?!allows7.g4!6...Nbd7?is met by7.Nc4!hitting the queen.7...Qa68.Ne3hitting both the queen and bishop on f5.8...Qa59.Bd2in view of the threat 10.Ncd5 Black is already lost, as they can't avoid the loss of material.} 
7. Nc4
7. Qd8 {The right response. Dropping back to c7 has the drawback the queen will soon be hit again by Qf3 and Bf4.} 
8. Ne3 {This has been played by some strong players, but I quite dislike it as the knight obstructs the bishop on c1.8.Bf4e69.Ne3Bg610.h4h611.h5Bh712.Qf3Bd6is pretty solid for Black in Antonov-Prokopchuk, Moscow 2018.8.Be2preparing either to castle or a quick g2-g4 (after Black plays ...e7-e6). The most reliable option for Black here is8...h6!?before aiming for our standard setup with ...e7-e6, ...Nbd7, ...Be7, ...O-O etc.} 
8. Bg6 {No need to block the e-pawn this time.} 
9. h4
9. h6
10. f4 {White's playing overambitiously here and we should be ready to punish it!} 
10. e6
11. g4 {This was played in Godena-Van der Werf, Montecatini Terme 2000. I am a fan of the text move coming up next.} 
11. Qc7 {Discouraging White to push his f-pawn further.} 
12. h5
12. Bh7
13. Qf3 {Covering some space behind the pawn front.} 
13. Bb4 {Pinning the knight and threatening ...Be4.} 
14. f5 {Looks as if White is very fast all of a sudden, but then} 
14. c5 {This is a fascinating counterblow. Any pawn exchanges would further open up the centre and I believe Black's pieces are better positioned for such an action. Frankly, the position remains incredibly complex and should still be playable for White, but I think we will have all the fun!} 
