16. Rxd2
16. cxd5 {This position was reached in Pikula-Zhukova, Belgrade 2000. Objectively speaking the position is still pretty equal, though I would rather be Black from a practical perspective.   The pawn on f7 is the only weakness, but can still easily be defended by the major pieces, while Black's active plan is based on improving its knight from g6 (via e7 to f5) and/or challenging White's weaknesses on the kingside with ...h7-h6, when the black rooks are going to participate actively as well.} 
