[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Ne5 c6 without 7.Bc4"]
[Black "5.Nf3 Bf5 6.Ne5 c6 7.g4 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Nf3 {The most logical move in terms of development has been the primary choice for White for quite some time. The knight is strategically positioned on f3, providing support to the pawn on d4. Meanwhile, others would opt to play it with the aim of swiftly building up pressure with Ne5.} 
5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Ne5 {The most aggressive option for White with various ideas like either placing the knight on c4, bringing the queen to f3 or opt for a quick g2-g4. We have to be alert now!} 
6. c6 {The key move so that the black queen will never be trapped.6...e6?!allows7.g4!6...Nbd7?is met by7.Nc4!hitting the queen.7...Qa68.Ne3hitting both the queen and bishop on f5.8...Qa59.Bd2in view of the threat 10.Ncd5 Black is already lost, as they can't avoid the loss of material.} 
7. g4 {A thematical idea, but not one which we should fear in this case, as Black hasn't committed himself yet to the move ...e7-e6.} 
7. Be6 {The safest square for the bishop, from where it both controls the d5-square as well as it keeps an eye on the pawn on g4.} 
8. h3 {A soft continuation and our response is no different than in other lines.} 
8. Nbd7
9. Nc4
9. Qc7 {Another option is to take on c4 followed by ...e6, but I like this even better.} 
10. Qf3
10. Nd5 {Stopping Bf4.} 
11. Ne4
11. h6 {11...g6!?in modern times we would consider this dynamic option, not fearing12.Ng5Bg713.Nxe6fxe6with pressure against the d-pawn, while undoubling the pawns by means of ...e6-e5 remains a reasonable plan as well.} 
12. Bd2
12. g6 {With a good game for Black in Vasiukov-Kholmov, Tbilisi 1976. Presumably, White is going to castle queenside and ambitious players should consider playing with opposite castled kings.   I believe Black is also pretty fast generating counterplay with the help of the b-pawn.} 
