5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Ne5 {The most aggressive option for White with various ideas like either placing the knight on c4, bringing the queen to f3 or opt for a quick g2-g4. We have to be alert now!} 
6. c6 {The key move so that the black queen will never be trapped.6...e6?!allows7.g4!6...Nbd7?is met by7.Nc4!hitting the queen.7...Qa68.Ne3hitting both the queen and bishop on f5.8...Qa59.Bd2in view of the threat 10.Ncd5 Black is already lost, as they can't avoid the loss of material.} 
7. Bf4 {7.Bc4is White's main move and will be covered in the next chapter.} 
7. Nbd7 {7...e6?!should again rather be avoided, on account of8.g4!} 
8. Nc4 {The principled reaction, as trading off pieces eases Black's task.} 
8. Qd8 {The only move8...Qa6?runs into the discovered check9.Nd6+.} 
9. d5
9. cxd5
10. Ne3
10. Be6 {The provocative10...Be4!?with the idea of11.f3e5is also worth investigating and leads to complex play.} 
11. Qd2
11. Nh5 {A small improvement upon a high-profile game. I think it makes sense to deprive White of his dark-squared bishop.} 
12. Ncxd5
12. Bxd5 {12...Nxf4?13.Nxf4leads to problems for Black.} 
13. Nxd5
13. Nxf4
14. Nxf4 {Clearing the d-file and White is concrete plans of increasing the pressure on the knight on d7 by means of O-O-O and Bb5.} 
14. Qc7
15. O-O-O {15.Nd5?!Qe5+is unproblematic.} 
15. O-O-O
16. Nd5
16. Qd6 {Preparing ...e7-e6 and go for the exchange of queens.} 
17. Qc3+ {Clearing the d-file to set up a potential discovered attack by the knight on d5 against Black’s queen.} 
17. Qc5 {Since the queen wasn’t doing particularly well on d6 it makes sense to move it away.} 
18. Qf3 {Attacking the pawn on f7 and avoiding the exchange of queens which would be perfectly fine for Black.} 
18. Ne5 {Attacking the queen and opening up the path for the rook.} 
19. Qf5+ {Double attack.} 
19. e6 {Counterattack!} 
20. Qxe5
20. Rxd5 {Black is eventually going to end up with an isolated pawn on d5. In most cases, you are supposed to keep pieces on the board when playing with an IQP. However, White’s queen on e5 is pretty active so it does make sense to aim for simplifications.} 
21. Rxd5
21. Qxd5
22. Qxd5
22. exd5 {With an equal endgame. Black will bring out the bishop to c5(attacking the pawn on f2), followed by moves like ...Re8 and ...Kc7. Black is active enough to compensate for the pawn weakness on d5.} 
