5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Ne5
6. c6 {The key move so that the black queen will never be trapped.6...e6?!allows7.g4!6...Nbd7?is met by7.Nc4!hitting the queen.7...Qa68.Ne3hitting both the queen and bishop on f5.8...Qa59.Bd2in view of the threat 10.Ncd5 Black is already lost, as they can't avoid the loss of material.} 
7. Bc4 {White hits the pawn on f7 and forces Black to reply with:} 
7. e6
8. g4 {The principled follow-up. After other moves Black's task is relatively simple as he plans to offer the exchange of knights with ...Nd7.8.Qe2Nbd79.Bd2see 8.Bd2.} 
8. Bg6 {8...Be4has been played here as well, but the text provokes White to further weaken the kingside with h2-h4.} 
9. h4
9. Nbd7 {9...Ne4?is badly timed here, as it runs into10.Qf3!Nxc311.bxc3and the threat of h4-h5 highlights the vulnerable spot on f7.11...Nd712.Nxd7Kxd713.h5and White wins.} 
10. Nxd7 {White first has to remove the threat of Black taking on e5, alternatives simply fail:10.Nxg6?!hxg6is harmless. In fact, White may regret soon having weakened the kingside prematurely.} 
10. Nxd7 {10...Kxd7is not as bad as it looks at first sight, but there is no reason to deviate from the main line.} 
11. h5 {Harassing the bishop is essential.11.Bd2is indecisive and enables Black to solidify the kingside with11...h5!establishing full control of the light squares.} 
11. Be4
12. Rh3 {This is the main alternative and was seen in the famous game Anand-Lautier, Biel 1997, a classic everyone should know! Fortunately for us, Scandinavian lovers, a very important improvement upon that game has been found.} 
12. Bg2 {12...Bd5has been played here as well, but the text is more clever, chasing the rook to an inferior square before dropping back to d5.} 
13. Re3
13. Bd5
14. Bf1 {14.Bd3can be met now by14...c5!White no longer covers the pawn on d4 with the queen.15.dxc5Bxc5with excellent play for Black.14.Bxd5cxd5is pretty harmless and invites Black to develop some play on the queenside with ...Rc8, ...Nb6 etc.14.Be2O-O-Othe king is safe and the rook is eyeing the queen along the d-file and thus aiming for ...e6-e5 strongly comes into consideration.} 
14. O-O-O
15. Bd2
15. Qb6 {This seems unproblematic for Black. If White is going to take on d5 Black is supposed to recapture with the e-pawn, intending to follow up with ...Bd6 with a very solid position.} 
