6. Ne5
6. c6 {The key move so that the black queen will never be trapped.6...e6?!allows7.g4!6...Nbd7?is met by7.Nc4!hitting the queen.7...Qa68.Ne3hitting both the queen and bishop on f5.8...Qa59.Bd2in view of the threat 10.Ncd5 Black is already lost, as they can't avoid the loss of material.} 
7. Bc4 {White hits the pawn on f7 and forces Black to reply with:} 
7. e6
8. g4 {The principled follow-up. After other moves Black's task is relatively simple as he plans to offer the exchange of knights with ...Nd7.8.Qe2Nbd79.Bd2see 8.Bd2.} 
8. Bg6 {8...Be4has been played here as well, but the text provokes White to further weaken the kingside with h2-h4.} 
9. h4
9. Nbd7 {9...Ne4?is badly timed here, as it runs into10.Qf3!Nxc311.bxc3and the threat of h4-h5 highlights the vulnerable spot on f7.11...Nd712.Nxd7Kxd713.h5and White wins.} 
10. Nxd7 {White first has to remove the threat of Black taking on e5, alternatives simply fail:10.Nxg6?!hxg6is harmless. In fact, White may regret soon having weakened the kingside prematurely.} 
10. Nxd7 {10...Kxd7is not as bad as it looks at first sight, but there is no reason to deviate from the main line.} 
11. h5 {Harassing the bishop is essential.11.Bd2is indecisive and enables Black to solidify the kingside with11...h5!establishing full control of the light squares.} 
11. Be4
12. O-O {Welcome to modern opening theory: White launches first both the g- and h-pawn before castling kingside!} 
12. Bd5
13. Nxd5 {If White wants something the bishop should be taken at some point anyway.} 
13. cxd5
14. Bd3 {Here is the bishop better placed, operating on two diagonals.} 
14. Bd6 {The most natural square for the bishop.} 
15. Qf3 {The queen seems to be well placed, but Black's next move is a shocker!} 
15. O-O-O {Bringing the king to a much safer place and connecting the rooks.} 
16. Be3
 {INFORMATIONAL} 16. g6 {Magnus' choice is the thematical way of developing active play on the kingside, but here it feels a bit shaky.} 
17. h6 {17.b4!with the idea of opening the b-file to double the rooks is critical. Black is advised not to accept the gift.17...Qa417...Qc7?runs into18.c4!18...dxc419.Bxc4Kb820.Rac1and Black is under pressure.18.Qxf7Rde8and although White seems to be better, the position remains very a mess and potentially could offer Black some nice attacking chances of the kingside.} 
17. Rhf8
18. a3 {Too slow.} 
18. f5
19. c4
19. e5 {Amazing to see how quickly the board turns into chaos!} 
20. b4 {20.Qxd5but after the exchange of queens with20...Qxd521.cxd5e4!Black plans to regain the pawn on d5 with an excellent game.} 
20. Qc7
21. c5
21. Be7
22. Bb5
22. e4
23. Qh3
23. f4 {With a huge initiative for Black in Firouzja-Carlsen, chess24.com 2021.} 
