13. Nxd5 {If White wants something the bishop should be taken at some point anyway.} 
13. cxd5
14. Bd3 {Here is the bishop better placed, operating on two diagonals.} 
14. Bd6 {The most natural square for the bishop.} 
15. Bd2 {This move has been recommended by both Indian top grandmasters Adhiban & Sethuraman in their respective 1.e4 repertoire courses. Frankly they did a great job and this line probably caused me the most problems to make the Scandinavian playable for Black!} 
15. Qb6 {The most active square for the queen. I rather wouldn't go back to c7, for a reason which becomes clear very soon.} 
16. c3 {Protecting d4, while grabbing the pawn on b2 isn't attractive for Black on account of Rb1.} 
16. Bc7 {Vacating the d6-square for the queen, thus preparing to setup a battery of queen and bishop on the b8-h2 diagonal. The bishop also keeps an eye on the a5-pawn.   Moreover, Black postpones the decision on which side to castle which may confuse the opponent with which plan to choose. For instance, h5-h6 isn't attractive when the black king is still on e8 as we could simply launch a counterattack on the g-file.} 
17. f4
17. g6 {An interesting idea, trying to use the fact Black hasn't castled yet. Once the files are opened, the white king could easily get in trouble.} 
18. h6
18. Nf6
19. g5
19. Ng8 {Another advantage of not having castled yet.} 
20. Qa4+
20. Kd8 {And although Black has been forced to give up the right of castling his position is pretty solid. The king is relatively safe on d8, as it will take time for White to prepare the c3-c4 break (d4 could be hanging). The knight will come via e7 back into play, when it could decide to jump to f5 anytime or simply anticipate White's plans.} 
