[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Nf3 {The most logical move in terms of development has been the primary choice for White for quite some time. The knight is strategically positioned on f3, providing support to the pawn on d4. Meanwhile, others would opt to play it with the aim of swiftly building up pressure with Ne5.} 
5. Bf5 {The main continuation. The bishop is well placed on f5, controlling some important light squares.A more tempting continuation here is5...Bg4, but after6.h3!Black is in a big dilemma. After dropping back to h56...Bh5White seizes the initiative with7.g4!while surrendering the pair of bishops by taking on f3 makes White's life much easier.The main alternative is5...c6(enabling the queen to come back home whenever it's needed) which brings us back to the old main line, but will not be part of our repertoire. Instead with the text, Black intends to play ...e7-e6 and put the dark-squared bishop on b4. Hence, for now, Black better omits the move ...c7-c6.} 
6. Ne5
6. c6 {The key move so that the black queen will never be trapped.6...e6?!allows7.g4!6...Nbd7?is met by7.Nc4!hitting the queen.7...Qa68.Ne3hitting both the queen and bishop on f5.8...Qa59.Bd2in view of the threat 10.Ncd5 Black is already lost, as they can't avoid the loss of material.} 
7. Bc4 {White hits the pawn on f7 and forces Black to reply with:} 
7. e6
8. g4 {The principled follow-up. After other moves Black's task is relatively simple as he plans to offer the exchange of knights with ...Nd7.8.Qe2Nbd79.Bd2see 8.Bd2.} 
8. Bg6 {8...Be4has been played here as well, but the text provokes White to further weaken the kingside with h2-h4.} 
9. h4
9. Nbd7 {9...Ne4?is badly timed here, as it runs into10.Qf3!Nxc311.bxc3and the threat of h4-h5 highlights the vulnerable spot on f7.11...Nd712.Nxd7Kxd713.h5and White wins.} 
10. Nxd7 {White first has to remove the threat of Black taking on e5, alternatives simply fail:10.Nxg6?!hxg6is harmless. In fact, White may regret soon having weakened the kingside prematurely.} 
10. Nxd7 {10...Kxd7is not as bad as it looks at first sight, but there is no reason to deviate from the main line.} 
11. h5 {Harassing the bishop is essential.11.Bd2is indecisive and enables Black to solidify the kingside with11...h5!establishing full control of the light squares.} 
11. Be4
12. O-O {Welcome to modern opening theory: White launches first both the g- and h-pawn before castling kingside!} 
12. Bd5
13. Nxd5 {If White wants something the bishop should be taken at some point anyway.} 
13. cxd5
14. Bd3 {Here is the bishop better placed, operating on two diagonals.} 
14. Bd6 {The most natural square for the bishop.} 
15. Bd2 {This move has been recommended by both Indian top grandmasters Adhiban & Sethuraman in their respective 1.e4 repertoire courses. Frankly they did a great job and this line probably caused me the most problems to make the Scandinavian playable for Black!} 
15. Qb6 {The most active square for the queen. I rather wouldn't go back to c7, for a reason which becomes clear very soon.} 
16. c3 {Protecting d4, while grabbing the pawn on b2 isn't attractive for Black on account of Rb1.} 
16. Bc7 {Vacating the d6-square for the queen, thus preparing to setup a battery of queen and bishop on the b8-h2 diagonal. The bishop also keeps an eye on the a5-pawn.   Moreover, Black postpones the decision on which side to castle which may confuse the opponent with which plan to choose. For instance, h5-h6 isn't attractive when the black king is still on e8 as we could simply launch a counterattack on the g-file.} 
17. a4
17. O-O {17...Qxb2?is met by18.a5!when the black queen is unable to return.} 
18. h6 {18.Qe2?!allows18...e5!and with the opening of the centre Black obtains excellent counterplay.} 
18. g6
19. a5
19. Qc6 {Preparing ...e6-e5.} 
20. f4 {Up to this point we are still following Adhiban's analysis, but I think I have managed to find an improvement for Black.} 
20. b5 {The queen on c6 helps Black set up a blockade on the queenside, making it hard for White to open up a second front over there.The Beast only mentions20...Nf6with the idea of jumping to e4, but that seems premature. We will keep that idea in the back of our mind though.} 
21. axb6
21. Qxb6 {Black is planning ...a7-a5 with some play against White's b-pawn.} 
22. Ra6 {22.b4a5!⇆gives Black sufficient play counterplay.} 
22. Qxb2
23. Qe2 {Threatening to trap the queen with Rb1.} 
23. Qb7 {White has to prove compensation for the pawn.} 
24. f5
24. exf5
25. gxf5
25. Rae8 {With a sharp game in which anything can happen. Due to the exposed king, White's position isn't without risk either.} 
