5. Bd2 {This move holds a considerable amount of venom, demanding caution with our queen in this line. Additionally, White delays the decision on how to develop their kingside pieces, which means we cannot simply revert to lines stemming from the Nf3-Bf5 setup.} 
5. Bg4 {By developing the bishop to this square we are provoking White to make a concession.} 
6. Nf3 {This move looks strange to me, why would one voluntarily place the knight in a pin? On the other hand, there can't be much wrong with developing a piece...} 
6. Qf5 {We are here to break the opening rules again by playing for the third time with our queen!} 
7. Bd3
7. Bxf3
8. gxf3 {A most challenging move to face.} 
8. Qd7
9. Ne4 {A relevant improvement, as White improves the knight and is ready to protect the pawn on d4 with the move c2-c3.} 
9. e6 {Aiming for a quick ...c7-c5.9...Qxd4might still be an option, but frankly, I didn't fancy trying to make this playable for Black with a long sequence of only moves to stay in the game.9...Nc610.c3e6A slightly more passive version, but possible too.} 
10. c3
10. c5 {The point of postponing ...Nc6 in this case. White can't capture on c5 as the bishop on d3 is hanging.} 
11. Nxf6+
11. gxf6
12. Be3
12. cxd4
13. Bxd4
13. Be7 {White is a bit better thanks to his pair of bishops, but Black has a clear plan to play Nc6, O-O-O and put the queen on c7. When given the chance, trading off the dark-squared bishops would be nice. Moreover, White's fractured pawn formation on the queenside may become a source of counterplay in the long run for Black.} 
