8. Nf3
8. a6 {I'd like to follow the only correspondence game which featured this position. Black is aiming for a quick ...Nc6, attacking the pawn on d4 and there is no time to be wasted by playing first our pawn to e6. By playing ...a7-a6 first we no longer have to fear our queen getting trapped by Na4, as a7 is still an escape square.} 
