6. f3 {The critical move.} 
6. Bd7 {After provoking White to make a concession with f2-f3, we happily retreat with our bishop to d7 and keep it within the chain, as ...e7-e6 will be played soon.   Due to a lack of space for our minor pieces, this is not entirely ideal, but dropping back with the bishop to either h5 or f5 would have invited White to keep harassing our light-squared bishop with an early g2-g4.} 
7. Bc4 {The most active square for the bishop and White threatens to win material by means of Nd5.} 
7. Qb6 {Avoiding the tactic as the queen is reasonably safe on b6.} 
8. Nge2 {The only serious challenge and quite a natural move in fact. White develops the last minor piece and secures the pawn on d4 at the same time.} 
8. e6 {8...Nc6??is the move we would like to play but it unfortunately allows White to play9.Na4!when the queen has been trapped. And yes, I have made this blunder once myself as well, but fortunately for me it was just an informal game :)} 
9. Bb3 {Like on the previous move, this idea is too cautious and doesn't pose Black any serious questions.} 
9. Nc6 {This is actually a very reasonable option too. Now that White's light-squared bishop no longer controls the squares a6 and b5, White's move Na4 doesn't trap the queen.} 
10. Be3
10. Na5 {Another idea behind Black's setup is to trade off the knight for the bishop which was seen in the game Anand-Van Wely, Wijk aan Zee 2013. I think Black doesn't have anything to complain about right now.} 
