9. O-O {The most natural move in the position, but I think it's less critical than9.Be3. However, note that now9...Qxb2?is significantly worse, in view of10.Rb1followed by taking on b7, as castling kingside is obviously more useful than playing for the second time with the bishop.} 
9. Be7 {A simple developing move, which actually deserves a bit more explanation. One of the main objectives for Black is playing ...c7-c5 and trading White's d-pawn. In general, this exchange of pawns should be considered fine for Black.However, the immediate9...c5?!is risky, in view of10.d5!when Black would rather have the bishop already on e7 to quickly get away with the king out of the centre.} 
10. a4
10. a5 {Bringing White's a-pawn to halt and thus securing the queen on b6. This move has been played in the majority of games and makes perfect sense. In the long run the b4-square may be used as an outpost for one of Black's pieces.10...Nc6?Black isn't advised to ignore the a-pawn with this move, as it runs into11.a5!Nxa512.Rxa5!Qxa513.Nd5Qxd514.Bxd5Nxd515.c4±and Black didn't have sufficient compensation for the queen in Nijboer-Van Wely, Germany 2013.} 
11. Be3
11. Na6 {A small refinement upon earlier games in which Black decided to castle immediately.} 
12. Qd2 {This is too soft.} 
12. c5 {With a good game for Black, as Black is about to play ...Bc6 and put the rook on d8. It turns out the queen isn't well placed on the d-file.} 
13. d5
13. Rd8 {And Black is absolutely fine. Black is about to play ...Bc6 and take advantage of the misplaced queen on d2.} 
