[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Bd2
5. Bg4
6. f3 {The critical move.} 
6. Bd7 {After provoking White to make a concession with f2-f3, we happily retreat with our bishop to d7 and keep it within the chain, as ...e7-e6 will be played soon.   Due to a lack of space for our minor pieces, this is not entirely ideal, but dropping back with the bishop to either h5 or f5 would have invited White to keep harassing our light-squared bishop with an early g2-g4.} 
7. Bc4 {The most active square for the bishop and White threatens to win material by means of Nd5.} 
7. Qb6 {Avoiding the tactic as the queen is reasonably safe on b6.} 
8. Nge2 {The only serious challenge and quite a natural move in fact. White develops the last minor piece and secures the pawn on d4 at the same time.} 
8. e6 {8...Nc6??is the move we would like to play but it unfortunately allows White to play9.Na4!when the queen has been trapped. And yes, I have made this blunder once myself as well, but fortunately for me it was just an informal game :)} 
9. Be3 {White is playing for the second time with the dark-squared bishop, but nevertheless, this seems to be the most challenging continuation. The bishop is doing well on e3, controlling the a7-g1 diagonal and is always looking for opportunities targeting the queen on b6 with a timed d4-d5.   A second idea is that by leaving the d2-sqaure free, the white queen is able to move forward, most likely to d3 where it's harmoniously placed by keeping all minor pieces protected and enabling the white king to castle queenside.} 
9. Qxb2 {A novelty on move 9 in a very well-known position is pretty cool!   True, taking a pawn on b2 always involves some risk, but in my opinion in this case it's negligible.   However, what follows now is a huge piece of fresh analysis and I would totally understand if you would decide to skip this part and opt for a more solid continuation. However, once I started analyzing this new territory I couldn't stop and decided that it was interesting enough to share with you guys!} 
10. Rb1
10. Qa3
11. Rb3 {Before capturing the pawn on b7, White tries to lure the black queen to an inferior square.} 
11. Qe7 {The queen is temporarily not doing well here, obstructing the bishop on f8, but at least the queen is safe now. I think White's following move is pretty much forced as otherwise Black happily secures the extra pawn with ...b7-b6.} 
12. Rxb7
12. Bc6
13. Qb1 {A tricky attempt, as White threatens to take the knight on b8 and it can't escape via d7 as that hangs the pawn on c7, while taking the rook on b7 obviously loses a piece.} 
13. Qd8 {The only move, but one which we were likely to play anyway as finally the dark-squared bishop can be developed.} 
14. Bb5
14. Bd7 {Although taking on b5 straightaway isn't disastrous, the exclamation has been added since we would like to decide under which conditions the bishops are getting swapped.} 
15. Bxd7+
15. Nbxd7
16. Nb5
16. Bd6 {The pawn on c7 has to be protected.} 
17. Nxa7 {isn't much of a problem as White isn't well coordinated.} 
17. O-O {White's extra pawn isn't worth much and I believe Black has various ideas of either:   1) trapping the rook with ...Nb6.   2) opening the centre with ...e6-e5.} 
