[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 5.Bc4 Bg4"]
[Black "5.Bc4 Bg4 6.Nge2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Bc4 {The second most popular move (after5.Nf3) is a very logical one. The bishop is nicely placed on c4 from where it attacks the pawn on f7 and takes away some valuable light squares from the black pieces. Note that often play may transpose to lines starting with5.Bd2.} 
5. Bg4 {Like in the line with 5.Bd2 I think this provocative move makes quite a lot of sense and it fits best with our repertoire.} 
6. Nge2 {The most natural alternative to 6.f3.White retains the possibility of chasing the bishop with f2-f3 after which the knight can decide to harass the bishop either from f4 or g3, depending on where the bishop goes.} 
6. e6 {The most sensible continuation, basically abandoning the idea of pressurizing the d-pawn with our standard plan of ...Nc6 and castling queenside, as often we would like to get our pawn to e5 in one go.} 
7. Bd2 {The setup with Bd2-Nc3 and Bc4 creates the threat of winning material by means of Nd5.} 
7. Qb6 {The best response, similar to line4.d4Nf65.Bd2Bg46.f3Bd77.Bc4when7...Qb6!is also the recommended move.7...c6??is a grave error, in view of8.f3!Bf59.g4!Bg610.h4threatening to trap the bishop.10...h611.Nf4!with the idea of taking on g6 after which e6 is going to fall.11...Bh712.Qe2+-and Black is totally busted.} 
8. f3 {The most aggressive option, I don't think there is anything to be gained from something like8.O-Owhen Black will place the pawn on c6 and the knight on d7, with a rock-solid formation.} 
8. Bf5
9. g4 {Consistently played.} 
9. Bg6
10. h4 {There is no way back for White.} 
10. h5 {In most games Black played10...h6, but our choice fixes the kingside and is more challenging.} 
11. g5
11. Nfd7
12. Nf4
12. Nc6 {Absolutely crucial to try to land with the knight on d4 rather than the queen. Secondly, Black may now consider castling queenside.} 
13. d5 {Aiming to break open the centre and install a knight on d5, which attacks both the queen and pawn on c7.} 
13. Nd4 {The knight is excellently placed on d4, eyeing the pawn on c2.} 
14. dxe6 {Things are heating up now, as White is almost breaking through. Taking with the knight on c2 doesn't lead anywhere after White places the king on f1.} 
14. Ne5 {A fantastic resource as the black knights are taking over in the centre! The pawn on f3 is a clear target now.} 
15. exf7+
15. Bxf7
16. Bxf7+
16. Kxf7 {Despite being a pawn down I believe it's Black who has managed to seize the initiative.} 
