5. Bc4 {The second most popular move (after5.Nf3) is a very logical one. The bishop is nicely placed on c4 from where it attacks the pawn on f7 and takes away some valuable light squares from the black pieces. Note that often play may transpose to lines starting with5.Bd2.} 
5. Bg4 {Like in the line with 5.Bd2 I think this provocative move makes quite a lot of sense and it fits best with our repertoire.} 
6. Nge2 {The most natural alternative to 6.f3.White retains the possibility of chasing the bishop with f2-f3 after which the knight can decide to harass the bishop either from f4 or g3, depending on where the bishop goes.} 
6. e6 {The most sensible continuation, basically abandoning the idea of pressurizing the d-pawn with our standard plan of ...Nc6 and castling queenside, as often we would like to get our pawn to e5 in one go.} 
7. f3 {Basically now and in the next few moves White can decide to insert the moves Bd2 and Qb6 which transposes to lines examined after7.Bd2.Let's now focus on what happens in case White refrains from developing the bishop to d2.} 
7. Bf5
8. g4
8. Bg6
9. h4
9. h5 {Like in the variation with 7.Bd2, Black mainly opted for the plan of saving the bishop with h7-h6, but I would rather make a case for advancing the h-pawn two squares.Note that if White now goes for10.g5Black can safely put the knight on d5, whereas in the other line, White is controlling that square too many times.} 
10. Nf4
10. Nc6 {It's absolutely key to get all our pieces involved as quickly as possible rather than going after some irrelevant pawns on the kingside.10...hxg4?there is no time for taking this pawn, in view of11.Nxg6fxg612.Qe2→Black is not in time to the king to a safer place to hide.} 
11. g5
11. Nd5 {A very important resource. Black is ready to sacrifice a pawn.} 
12. Nxg6
12. fxg6
13. Bd2
13. Bb4
14. Nxd5
14. exd5
15. Bd3
15. O-O {Definitely the way to go if you are looking for action! Black has quite some strong threats like ...Rae8 and/or taking on d2 intending to win the pawn on f3. Play becomes much sharper again!} 
16. c3
16. Rae8+
17. Kf2 {A more active spot for the king and now both the bishop on b4 as well as the pawn on g6 are hanging.} 
17. Nxd4 {A remarkable tactical idea! The knight can't be taken as then Black captures the bishop on d2.} 
18. Rh3 {Protecting the pawn on f3.} 
18. c5 {What?? The two minor pieces are hanging and Black can get away with this move?} 
19. cxb4
19. Qc7 {By bringing the queen back to c7 we renew the idea of taking on f3, deflecting the white rook covering the h2-square. Apparently, Black is doing fine (0.00) which is confirmed by the following forcing variation:} 
20. Bf1
20. Nxf3
21. Rxf3
21. Qh2+
22. Bg2
22. Rxf3+
23. Qxf3
23. Rf8
24. Qxf8+
24. Kxf8
25. Rh1 {Defending the pawn on h4.} 
25. Qe5 {With a centralized queen there are always a bunch of checks and ideas of wrapping up some of White's pawns. White isn't fully coordinated yet.} 
