[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Bc4 {The second most popular move (after5.Nf3) is a very logical one. The bishop is nicely placed on c4 from where it attacks the pawn on f7 and takes away some valuable light squares from the black pieces. Note that often play may transpose to lines starting with5.Bd2.} 
5. Bg4 {Like in the line with 5.Bd2 I think this provocative move makes quite a lot of sense and it fits best with our repertoire.} 
6. Qd3 {Kind of a weird move, as sooner or later White got to make a choice on how to develop the kingside anyway. The queen is actually not doing too well on d3. Once the bishop gets attacked with f2-f3 or h2-h3, it drops back with tempo to f5, hitting the queen. Hence, we can simply continue with our developing scheme.} 
6. Nc6 {Preparing to castle.} 
7. Bb5 {7.Bd2?preparing to castle queenside, allows7...Nb4!-+ and since the white queen isn't able to keep c2 defended, Black wins a huge amount of material.} 
7. O-O-O {Anyway!} 
8. Bxc6
8. bxc6 {Now both ...e7-e5 and ...c6-c5 are unpleasant threats White has to reckon with.} 
9. Nf3
9. c5
10. d5
10. e6 {And the pawn is in the pocket.} 
11. Ne5
11. Rxd5
