[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Bc4 {The second most popular move (after5.Nf3) is a very logical one. The bishop is nicely placed on c4 from where it attacks the pawn on f7 and takes away some valuable light squares from the black pieces. Note that often play may transpose to lines starting with5.Bd2.} 
5. Bg4 {Like in the line with 5.Bd2 I think this provocative move makes quite a lot of sense and it fits best with our repertoire.} 
6. f3
6. Bd7 {Other bishop moves have been tried here as well, but from a practical perspective, I'd rather not bother you with these lines.  Both on h5 and f5 the bishop can easily be targeted and may cause some practical problems to solve early on. With the text, Black actually plays in the same style as I recommended in the line with4.d4Nf65.Bd2.} 
7. Be3 {Already at this point we are at unexplored territory and therefore I think the following idea is worth testing.} 
7. Nc6 {Trying to get in a quick ...e7-e5, not wasting time by playing the pawn to e6 first.} 
8. d5 {8.Nge2e5!getting in this move at once seemed quite attractive!9.d5Ne7!?⇆ with the idea of ...Nf5 and bringing out the dark-squared bishop.} 
8. Ne5
9. Bb3
9. e6 {Freeing the bishop from f8.} 
10. Qd4 {The critical move, as White aims to prove the instability of the knight on e5.10.dxe6?Bxe611.Bxe6fxe6∓and Black obtains tremendous piece play as compensation for the isolated e-pawn.} 
10. Bd6
11. Bf4
11. Nxd5 {Initiating some tactical play.} 
12. Bxd5
12. c5 {A very important zwischenzug, as otherwise the knight on e5 is just lost.} 
13. Qe3
13. exd5
14. Bxe5
14. O-O-O {Another fantastic idea, trying to take advantage of the pin along the e-file.} 
15. Bxd6
15. Rhe8
16. Be5
16. d4 {First, we should try to win the knight.16...f6?doesn't have the desirable effect, because of17.Qd2!unpinning the knight on c317...Rxe5+18.Nge2+-and White eventually consolidates.} 
17. Qf4
17. g5 {Chasing the queen to an inferior square.} 
18. Qxg5
18. c4 {The point! Had the queen been still on f4, White could have captured the pawn on d4. Black is temporarily down two pieces, but about to regain both of them by first taking on c3 followed by ...Rxe5.} 
19. f4
19. dxc3 {Threatening a discovered check by taking on b2.} 
20. bxc3
20. Rxe5+
21. Qxe5 {Forced, as21.fxe5is met by21...Qxc3winning the rook.} 
21. Re8
22. Qxe8+
22. Bxe8 {From a material point of view White is better with two rooks and a pawn for the queen. However, the king is still in the center and Black threatens to take on c3.} 
23. Ne2
23. Ba4
24. Rc1 {24.O-O-O ?is met by24...Bxc2!25.Kxc2Qxa2+26.Kc1Qxe2-+and black is technically winning.} 
24. Qf5 {The queen is just stronger than the two rooks and therefore I think this endgame remains very unpleasant for White.} 
