1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. d4 {This flexible move is White's main continuation. Before developing any of the minor pieces White places the remaining centre pawn.} 
4. Nf6 {Basically the only square for the knight. Depending on White's next move, Black will bring the light-squared bishop into the game (either to f5 or g4) before putting the pawn on e6.} 
5. Bd3 {This move has rarely been played and for a good reason. Although the bishop itself isn't that badly placed on d3, it's surely less active here compared with lines where it goes to c4. However, the main problem is the vulnerability of White's d-pawn which is no longer protected by the queen.} 
5. Nc6 {5...Bf5?6.Qf3±and now the only move to avoid an immediate disaster is going back with the bishop to c8.} 
6. Nf3
6. Bg4 {Pinning the knight and planning to take on d4 next.In the case of7.Bb5play transposes to the line5.Bc4Bg46.Nf3Nc67.Bb5.} 
7. Bd2 {Relatively the best way to deal with the pawn weakness on d4.7.Be3?O-O-Othe pressure against the d-pawn is immense(8.Be2runs into8...e5!)8.O-Oe5!and White's centre collapses.} 
7. O-O-O {White's two bishops on the d-file aren't doing a lot, while the pressure against White's d-pawn only increases. White may consider moving the knight from c3 somewhere, attacking the queen on a5, but there are still quite a number of attractive squares, e.g. h5 or d5, to keep White under pressure.7...Nxd4?fails to8.Nb5!Nxf3+9.gxf3+-and White wins a piece as both the queen and bishop on g4 are hanging.} 
8. Nb5 {The best try, as the bishop attacks the queen while the fifth rank is blocked.} 
8. Qb6 {Planning either to take straightaway on f3 (followed by the pawn on d4) or chase the knight away first with ...a7-a6.} 
9. a4 {To be able to meet9...a6with10.a5!when the black queen is trapped.} 
9. Bxf3 {We have to win the d-pawn.} 
10. Qxf3
10. Nxd4
11. Nxd4
11. Qxd4 {Black is pawn up and about to consolidate the position with ...e7-e6 and Qd5. White has to act quickly.} 
12. Be3 {Black isn't advised now taking on b2 as that opens the files towards the king.} 
12. Qd5
13. Qxd5
13. Nxd5
14. Bxa7 {Fischer's bishop? Well, unfortunately not really.We better refrain from14...b6which runs into15.Ba6and Black is no longer able to trap the bishop as White has ideas like attacking the knight on d5 with c2-c4 and eventually playing a4-a5 freeing the bishop from a7.} 
14. Nb4 {Intending to take on d3.} 
15. Be4
15. e6 {With the idea of ...f7-f5, deflecting the bishop from the pawn on c2.} 
16. c3
16. f5 {Anyway!} 
17. Be3
17. fxe4
18. cxb4
18. Bxb4+
19. Ke2
19. Rd3 {Black's extra pawn isn't worth a lot. White should be able to defend.} 
