5. Nc6 {5...Bf5?6.Qf3±and now the only move to avoid an immediate disaster is going back with the bishop to c8.} 
6. Be3
6. e5 {Since White has refrained from playing an early Nf3 Black has gained full control over the e5-square which justifies our pawnbreak. In case of 7.dxe5 Nxe5! Black obtains fantastic piece play.} 
7. Nge2
7. Bg4 {Once again, we would welcome the weakening f2-f3.} 
8. dxe5
8. Nxe5 {The open centre offers the side with the initiative usually the better prospects, which is this time is not different. However, with precise play White is able to hold the balance.} 
9. h3
9. Bh5 {Black to play would castle queenside and create a pawn weakness on d3, but White is in time solving the problems in a concrete manner.} 
10. Bb5+
10. c6
11. Qd4 {Another key move.} 
11. Ned7 {Keeping pieces on the board. If White moves the bishop Black has ...Bc5 with tempo.} 
12. Qa4 {By offering the exchange Black doesn't get a chance taking the bishop. Black has various ways to proceed, the simplest being} 
12. Qxa4
13. Bxa4
13. Bc5 {With a slightly more equal position for Black, though a draw is the likely outcome of the game.} 
