[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. Bc4 {A flexible move, as White postpones the decision whether to push the d-pawn one or two squares.} 
4. Nf6 {Following our main recipe. In the case of5.d4we are back in the lines arising from4.d4Nf65.Bc4.} 
5. d3 {This modest move has often been chosen by White players who wanted to avoid the main lines of the Scandinavian or simply had some bad experiences losing their pawn when it went to d4 :)   Jokes aside, this move contains more venom than it may appear at first and should be treated seriously.} 
5. Bg4 {I believe this is the most practical option, pretty much in the spirit of the mainline arising from4.d4Nf65.Bd2and5.Bc4.5...a6!?This rare pawn move has gained the highest recommendation from Stockfish and should objectively provide Black with the best opportunity to achieve complete equality.  Nevertheless, comprehending the intricacies of this configuration has proven challenging for me. After clicking a bit, going back and forth in my own analysis, I have reached the conclusion that it is an impractical choice, demanding near-flawless memorization skills.  I don't consider that to be ideal for most people, particularly when taking into account that Black deviates from the general opening principles (making excessive pawn moves, bringing the queen out early, etc.) and a single mistake will result in severe consequences.} 
6. Nge2 {By placing the knight on e2, White postpones the decision of how to challenge the bishop on g4. However, one of the drawbacks of this plan is that the knight can't be developed any longer to the more active square f3.} 
6. e6 {We have to realize that after this move we are no longer able to retreat the bishop to d7, like we in most lines where White plays an early f2-f3.} 
7. h3 {This is harmless and we shouldn't mind giving up our bishop for the knight.} 
7. Bxe2
8. Qxe2
8. Nc6 {Planning to castle queenside and install a knight on d4.} 
9. Bb5 {White attempts to chronically damage the queenside structure.} 
9. Nd5 {Counterattacking the knight on c3.} 
10. Bxc6+
10. bxc6
11. Bd2
11. Nxc3
12. Bxc3
12. Bb4 {Concrete play. If White plays13.Qd2everything can be swapped onc3when the remaining rook endgame is pretty drawish.} 
13. Bxb4
13. Qxb4+ {Hitting the pawn on b2.} 
14. c3
14. Qb5 {Despite the isolated doubled pawns on the c-file I think Black is OK. With all major pieces on the board, the activity of these pieces in combination with the king's safety is what matters more.} 
