6. Nge2 {By placing the knight on e2, White postpones the decision of how to challenge the bishop on g4. However, one of the drawbacks of this plan is that the knight can't be developed any longer to the more active square f3.} 
6. e6 {We have to realize that after this move we are no longer able to retreat the bishop to d7, like we in most lines where White plays an early f2-f3.} 
7. f3
7. Bf5
8. g4
8. Bg6 {9.Bd2transposes to the line with 7.Bd2.} 
9. Nf4
9. Nc6 {Preparing to castle and control the d4-square.} 
10. h4 {Going after the bishop on g6.} 
10. e5
11. Nxg6
11. hxg6 {White has managed to grab the bishop pair, but had to pay a high price for it as the kingside is overextended. However, the pawn on f7 has become more vulnerable since Black has played ...e6-e5. In order to castle queenside Black therefore first has to bring back the queen via c5 to e7 to protect the pawn on f7. An alternative plan may be just to ignore the f7-pawn and aim for quick development by castling queenside immediately, but frankly I don't think there is any need complicating matters.} 
