[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 4.b4, 4.Rb1, 4.g3 and 4.Qe2"]
[Black "4.g3 Nf6 5.Bg2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. g3 {The idea of fianchettoing the bishop is not very common against the Scandinavian, still it has been played by some very strong grandmasters. White attempts to exert pressure on the long diagonal and particular against the pawn on b7.} 
4. Nf6 {Like in the main lines covered in earlier chapter I'd like to start with this developing move.} 
5. Bg2 {The big question is how Black is going to arrange the queenside development.} 
5. e5 {White has refrained from occupying the centre with the d-pawn and therefore I believe it makes a lot of sense to take the opportunity grabbing space in the centre. Black doesn't mind an early contact of the two remaining central pawns. White has now to decide how to develop the knight from g1.} 
6. Nge2 {The knight is slighly more passive than on f3, but the h1-a8 diagonal remains open.} 
6. Bd6 {Overprotecting the pawn on e5.} 
7. O-O
7. O-O
8. d4 {Fighting back in the centre. White would like to see Black captures on d4 which would enable the knight to reach a more active square, but for Black there is no reason to react.} 
8. c6 {Neutralizing White's light-squared bishop, while the queen can always consider going back to c7.By the way, if White would take now on e5 Black recaptures with the bishop, as9.dxe5Qxe5?fails to10.Bf4when the bishop on d6 will be lost.} 
9. Bg5 {Threatening to destroy Black's pawn formation on the kingside.} 
9. Nbd7 {Solid reaction. It's not a big deal the knight on d7 temporarily blocks the bishop on c8, since after any calm move Black will question the bishop on g5 with ...h7-h6.} 
10. d5 {By advancing the pawn White aims to remove the pawn from c6 in order to gain control over the long diagonal and access to the d5-square. The following series of exchanges comes very naturally.} 
10. cxd5
11. Nxd5
11. Nxd5
12. Qxd5
12. Qxd5
13. Bxd5 {White's bishop on d5 is pretty dominant, but Black as an antidote.} 
13. h6 {First challenge the other one!} 
14. Be3
14. Nf6 {To unleash Black's pieces from the queenside.} 
15. Bg2
15. Ng4 {One more tempo, as White doesn't want the bishop to be exchanged.} 
16. Bd2
16. Bf5 {All opening problems are solved now. In case White ever captures on b7 Black will regain the pawn on b2. The queenless middlegame is very balanced.} 
