4. g3 {The idea of fianchettoing the bishop is not very common against the Scandinavian, still it has been played by some very strong grandmasters. White attempts to exert pressure on the long diagonal and particular against the pawn on b7.} 
4. Nf6 {Like in the main lines covered in earlier chapter I'd like to start with this developing move.} 
5. Bg2 {The big question is how Black is going to arrange the queenside development.} 
5. c6 {From a positional point of view this move makes a lot of sense, as Black diminishes the power of the light-squared bishop on g2. Black may proceed in the spirit of the Scandinavian by bringing the light-squared bishop out to either f5 or g4, and follow up with ...e7-e6, Nbd7 and Be7 etc.Compared with our main move5...e5!?immediate contact between the two central pawns will be postponed and might therefore be a more attractive option for those aiming for a slow battle. In any case, Black is very solid and obtains a perfectly playable position.} 
