4. b4 {A tricky gambit line. White's goal by sacrificing the b-pawn is to exert pressure down that file, particularly against the pawn on b7 and thus making it harder for Black completing the development on that side of the board.} 
4. Qxb4 {Let's accept the gambit and the challenge!} 
5. Rb1 {The most sensible continuation. By occupying the half-open b-file with the rook, White exerts pressure against the pawn on b7 which makes it harder for Black completing development on the queenside.} 
5. Qd6 {The safest square for the queen. The queen is well-placed on d6 from where it still can move in many different directions, including home (d8).} 
6. d4 {In order to prove compensation for the pawn White can't treat this position without this particular move. It should be said though that White could also have started with either6.Nf3or6.Bc4which presumably transposes to lines covered elsewhere.} 
6. Nf6 {The most natural developing move is Black's best try. In the high-profile game Nakamura-Firouzja, Black instead went for the immediate6...Qd8, but there is no reason to retreat the queen yet.} 
7. Bc4 {The bishop isn't well placed here, but Black shouldn't get tempted now by playing7...Qc6??which runs into8.Bb5!and the queen is lost.} 
7. a6 {Preparing ...b7-b5.} 
8. a4 {Stopping Black's idea to push the b-pawn.} 
8. Qc6 {Thanks to Black's previous move White can't play Bb5. Everything is hanging now.} 
9. Qd3
9. Qxg2 {Black wins a second pawn and not to make things worse White has to offer the exchange of queens on f3.} 
