[Black "4.b4 Qxb4 5.Rb1 #8"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nc3
3. Qa5
4. b4 {A tricky gambit line. White's goal by sacrificing the b-pawn is to exert pressure down that file, particularly against the pawn on b7 and thus making it harder for Black completing the development on that side of the board.} 
4. Qxb4 {Let's accept the gambit and the challenge!} 
5. Rb1 {The most sensible continuation. By occupying the half-open b-file with the rook, White exerts pressure against the pawn on b7 which makes it harder for Black completing development on the queenside.} 
5. Qd6 {The safest square for the queen. The queen is well-placed on d6 from where it still can move in many different directions, including home (d8).} 
6. d4 {In order to prove compensation for the pawn White can't treat this position without this particular move. It should be said though that White could also have started with either6.Nf3or6.Bc4which presumably transposes to lines covered elsewhere.} 
6. Nf6 {The most natural developing move is Black's best try. In the high-profile game Nakamura-Firouzja, Black instead went for the immediate6...Qd8, but there is no reason to retreat the queen yet.} 
7. Nf3
7. a6 {Black takes control over the b5-square, so we no longer have to worry about a possible knight jump. Another point is revealed on the next move.} 
8. g3 {A typical idea: White prepares the development of both the bishops to g2 and f4.} 
8. Qc6 {A remarkable multi-purpose idea, making one more move with the queen! First of all, Black gains time by attacking the knight and c3, but the queen is in general doing a great job on the a8-h1 diagonal as it protects the pawn on b7 as well as it pins the knight on f3. Evidently, this move wouldn't have been possible without ...a7-a6 as in that case White would have the opportunity winning the queen thanks to the pin with Bb5.} 
9. Qd3 {Protecting both knights, but the drawback is that the queen may become a target for the light-squared bishop.} 
9. Be6 {Trying to get a grip on the light-squares and preventing White from developing the bishop to g2 as that would run into ...Bc4.} 
10. Bg5 {With the idea of removing the knight from f6 in order to push the d-pawn.} 
10. Nbd7 {Overprotecting the knight and thus retaining control over the d5-square. White still can't move the bishop to g2 as that allows Black to put the bishop on c4. White has to act fast now, not giving Black a chance to establish a full grip on the central light squares with ...Nb6.} 
11. Bxf6
11. Nxf6
12. Bg2 {White is looking for a discovered attack on the queen.} 
12. g6 {12...Bc4?tactically fails to13.Ne5!!Qxg2(13...Bxd314.Nxc6followed by Rxb7 clearly favors White).14.Qxc4offers White a decisive attack.} 
13. Nh4 {The only discovered attack which keeps the bishop protected, but the knight is obviously not so well placed at the side of the board.} 
13. Qd6 {Not caring too much about that b7-pawn.} 
14. Bxb7
14. Rd8 {Keeping an eye on White's d-pawn.} 
15. Qxa6
15. Qxa6
16. Bxa6 {White is suddenly even a pawn up.} 
16. Bg7 {White's pawns aren't dangerous and rather than taking on d4 straightaway, Black is recommended to complete development and get the other rook into the game.} 
