3. Nf3 {The main alternative to3.Nc3. By developing first the king's knight White retains the option of playing both d2-d4 and c2-c4, grabbing more space and thus gaining more central influence.} 
3. Bg4 {The principled reaction. Black develops the light-squared bishop to the most active square by pinning the knight on f3.} 
4. Be2 {The most logical response, as White isn't willing to allow Black to double the f-pawns.} 
4. Nc6
5. Nc3
5. Qd7 {There is no need going on a journey with Her Majesty right now and d7 is the safest square to retreat. The queen is well placed on d7, as Black has already brought out the light-squared bishop.} 
6. d4 {The move d4-d5 is a bit of unpleasant idea to face.} 
6. e6 {An useful move and there is absolutely no need giving White the opportunity to push the d-pawn.} 
7. h3 {A natural move, but it does waste a valuable move which Black is going to use exerting pressure against the d-pawn.} 
7. Bxf3 {Dropping back to h5 is another possibility of course, but we have a concrete idea in mind of targetting the d-pawn.} 
8. Bxf3
8. O-O-O {Before taking on d4, Black protects the pawn on b7. White doesn't want to give up the d-pawn and therefore has to make the sad decision of trading off their own light-squared bishop or push the d-pawn.} 
9. Bxc6 {9.Be3Nxd4!∓is just a pawn.} 
9. Qxc6
10. O-O {White has managed to avoid an immediate disaster regarding the d-pawn, but Black is already very comfortable anyway having traded off two minor pieces. At first, it seems as if not much is going on, but the following plan is instructive.} 
10. Ne7 {A very important idea worth remembering for various types of positions arising from this opening. Since Black had not moved the king's knight yet, Black has the additional possibility of bringing it out via e7 to f5, pressurizing the pawn on d4.   The position is objectively equal, but I would rather be Black here. For instance, things could quickly go wrong for White:} 
11. Be3
11. Nf5
12. Ne2 {And now in Gastmeyer-Wanzek, Berlin 1996, strong would have been:} 
12. g5 {With the idea of making use of the hook on h3 by playing ...Rg8, ...g5-g4 (eventually prepared by ...h7-h5).} 
13. Bxg5 {This is not possible, because of:} 
13. Rg8
14. Qd2
14. h6 {And the rook on d8 can't be taken because of mate on g2.} 
