1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nf3 {The main alternative to3.Nc3. By developing first the king's knight White retains the option of playing both d2-d4 and c2-c4, grabbing more space and thus gaining more central influence.} 
3. Bg4 {The principled reaction. Black develops the light-squared bishop to the most active square by pinning the knight on f3.} 
4. Be2 {The most logical response, as White isn't willing to allow Black to double the f-pawns.} 
4. Nc6
5. O-O {With this specific move order White abandones the idea of getting a pawn on d4.} 
5. O-O-O {By castling queenside Black reinforces the control over the d4-square. Hence, White no longer has the option of playing d2-d4, because that runs into ...Bxf3 followed by taking the pawn on d4.} 
6. h3 {Combining this move with castling kingside seems strange to me. Black has a couple of playable possibilities, but lets try to exploit the chosen move-order!} 
6. h5 {This move has rarely been tried, but makes a lot of sense (as White has already castled) and will certainly scare off your opponent! White isn't recommended to take the bishop on g4 as that opens the h-file and likely will lead to a powerful attack for Black.} 
7. c3
7. Nf6
8. d4
8. e5
9. Be3 {9.dxe5Bxf310.Bxf3Qxe5is absolutely fine for Black, as White doesn't get a chance to employ its bishop pair yet.} 
9. Qd7 {The queen is vacating the d5-square for the knight in order to challenge the bishop on e3. Besides, in certain cases, Black may even consider sacrificing the bishop on h3.} 
10. Nxe5 {Aiming for simplifications.} 
10. Nxe5
11. dxe5
11. Qxd1
12. Bxd1
12. Bxd1 {Black prefers to keep all rooks on the board.} 
13. exf6
13. Ba4 {On the way to c6.} 
14. fxg7
14. Bxg7 {White is a pawn up, but Black is excellent compensation.} 
15. Nd2
15. Rhg8 {With the idea of pressurizing the pawn on g2. The black bishops will make White's life hard and I don't think there is clear plan for White utilizing the extra pawn.} 
