3. Bg4 {The principled reaction. Black develops the light-squared bishop to the most active square by pinning the knight on f3.} 
4. Be2 {The most logical response, as White isn't willing to allow Black to double the f-pawns.} 
4. Nc6
5. h3
5. Bxf3 {In other games Black has also decided to maintain the tension with ... Bh5, but our play is more concrete.} 
6. Bxf3
6. Qe6+ {This check is more precise than6...Qe5, providing Black an extra option besides the natural exchange of queens on e2 on the next move.} 
7. Qe2
7. Nd4 {This resource wouldn't have been available had the black queen been on e5 as in that case White could have simply taken it now.} 
8. Qxe6
8. Nxf3+ {An important zwischenzug, ruining White's pawn structure on the kingside.} 
9. gxf3 {9.Ke2??this 'clever' move aiming to recapture the knight with the king rather than weakening the pawn structure on the kingside, allows9...Nd4+!and thanks to this intermediate check Black wins a piece.} 
9. fxe6 {A remarkable position, as by move 9 both sides have already isolated doubled pawns.} 
10. d4 {The d-pawn will become a target now.} 
10. g6
11. Bf4 {This has been played in a few games. At first, f4 seems to be the most active square for the bishop, hitting the pawn on c7. On the other hand, the bishop is a clear target for the black pieces now.} 
11. O-O-O {Defending c7 and attacking the pawn on d4.} 
12. c3
12. Nf6
13. Nd2
13. Nh5 {Hitting the bishop on f4.} 
14. Be5 {14.Be3Bg7and Black will get in ...e6-e5.14.Bh2Bh6!∓ followed by ...Rhf8 when Black has ideas of doubling rooks on the f-file and/or using the f4-square for one of its minor pieces.} 
14. Bg7
15. Nc4 {Trying to retain control over the e5-square.} 
15. Rhf8
16. Ke2 {The knight no longer defends the pawn on f3, so the king has to do that now.} 
16. Bxe5
17. Nxe5
17. c5 {With fantastic play for Black. It's important to note that White can't take on c5:} 
18. dxc5 {The knight is no longer stable on e5.} 
18. Rf5
19. Nd3 {Sticking to the pawn on c5 introduces some new problems for White.19.Nc4Rxc520.Ne3Nf4+followed by ...Nd3 and White is in huge trouble.} 
19. Rfd5 {And White can't defend the knight with:} 
20. Rhd1
20. Rxd3
21. Rxd3
21. Nf4+
22. Ke3
22. Nxd3 {and Black is a piece up.} 
