1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nf3
3. Bg4
4. Be2
4. Nc6
5. d4 {The most ambitious and frequently played move. White is aiming to get in a quick c2-c4 and d4-d5, questioning the knight on c6. At the same time, the pawn on d4 offers Black counterplay in the centre and naturally play is becoming quite sharp in this line.} 
5. O-O-O {The tension in the centre increases every move! By castling queenside the black king has found a safe place, while the rook exerts pressure against the pawn on d4.} 
6. c3 {Solidifying the pawn on d4 is not White's most challenging move and offers Black an easy life. The downside is it doesn't the black queen on d5 and that it takes away the c3-square from the knight.} 
6. e5 {Since we are ahead slightly ahead in development, opening the centre is absolutely justified!} 
7. Be3 {This fits well into the concept of maintaining the pawn on d4, but it's rather passive.} 
7. Nh6 {The most energetic response is another great novelty! Black is intending to place the knight on f5, from where it exerts pressure on both the pawn on d4 and bishop on e3.} 
8. Bxh6 {Doubling the pawns on the h-file doesn't bring White any success. To the contrary, as the pawn on d4 becomes a new source of problems.} 
8. gxh6
9. O-O
9. Rg8 {A lovely move. Black maximizes the pressure on White's position by posting the rook on the g-file, introducing mating motifs on g2. Black threatens to to take twice on d4.} 
10. dxe5
10. Qe4 {A powerful move, hitting the queen on d1, while the queen also got to keep the knight on f3 defended.} 
11. Nbd2 {Counterattacking the queen on e4. Black may now even consider taking on d2 which eventually leads to a position with two minor pieces for the rook. Our idea is not bad either:} 
11. Qf4 {White is completely busted. By keeping queens on the board Black keeps the pressure high and with ideas like ...Bxf3 and/or ...Nxe5 it seems to me that soon White will have to give up material.} 
