6. c3 {Solidifying the pawn on d4 is not White's most challenging move and offers Black an easy life. The downside is it doesn't the black queen on d5 and that it takes away the c3-square from the knight.} 
6. e5 {Since we are ahead slightly ahead in development, opening the centre is absolutely justified!} 
7. c4
7. Qe4 {An ambitious move. The queen fearlessly ventures into the center, ready to capture either on f3 or d4.} 
8. Nc3 {Only move.} 
8. Bb4 {Pin!} 
9. d5 {The first new move, but otherwise the d-pawn will be lost.} 
9. Nf6
10. O-O {Now is the perfect time to eliminate the knight from the board.} 
10. Bxc3
11. bxc3
11. Na5 {This is a completely new position that promises an interesting game. White needs to be cautious to prevent the immediate collapse of the pawn center.} 
12. Bd3 {The queen is trapped?} 
12. Bxf3 {The key motif which is important to remember.} 
13. gxf3
13. Qh4 {White has to be very careful here. Black has several promising ideas:   - Win the pawn on c4.   - Activate the rook via the 6th rank.   - Play ...Rhe8 and try to break in the centre.} 
