3. Nf3
3. Bg4
4. Be2
4. Nc6
5. d4 {The most ambitious and frequently played move. White is aiming to get in a quick c2-c4 and d4-d5, questioning the knight on c6. At the same time, the pawn on d4 offers Black counterplay in the centre and naturally play is becoming quite sharp in this line.} 
5. O-O-O {The tension in the centre increases every move! By castling queenside the black king has found a safe place, while the rook exerts pressure against the pawn on d4.} 
6. Nc3
6. Qf5 {An attempt to keep more play in the position. Black is about to take on f3 and d4 after which the queen and knight are targetting the pawn on c2 as well.} 
7. d5 {With the idea of playing Bd3, threatening both the queen on f5 and the knight on c6.} 
7. Bxf3
8. Bxf3 {White threatens to win the queen by means of Bg4.} 
8. Nf6 {Very accurate, as inferior is8...e6which allows9.Be4!?.The knight covers three valuable squares g4, e4 and d5.} 
9. Be3
9. e6
10. Qe2 {In case of10...exd5White has the plan to follow-up with castling queenside and Qb5 when it is not clear if Black can stick to the extra pawn.} 
10. Ne5 {Much simpler. Black can take the bishop on f3 anytime.} 
11. dxe6
11. fxe6 {Despite the pawn weakness on e6, Black enjoys a very clear advantage. The bishop on f3 is badly placed and the queen on e2 has to keep that piece protected. Meanwhile, Black's next few moves are pretty clear: ...Bd6 & ...Rhf8 with excellent piece play.} 
