1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nf3
3. Bg4
4. Be2
4. Nc6
5. d4 {The most ambitious and frequently played move. White is aiming to get in a quick c2-c4 and d4-d5, questioning the knight on c6. At the same time, the pawn on d4 offers Black counterplay in the centre and naturally play is becoming quite sharp in this line.} 
5. O-O-O {The tension in the centre increases every move! By castling queenside the black king has found a safe place, while the rook exerts pressure against the pawn on d4.} 
6. Be3 {White protects the pawn on d4 one more time.} 
6. e5 {We are fighting back in the centre, undermining the pawn on d4 as well as getting ready to bring our dark-squared bishop out to b4 at the right moment.} 
7. dxe5 {A harmless capture, aiming for simplifications. Black has good ways obtaining full equality, but our choice is the most ambitious one.} 
7. Bxf3 {Removing the defender of the pawn on e5. White can't exchange queens, as the bishop will recapture on d5.} 
8. Bxf3
8. Qxe5 {Attacking both the queen on d1 as well as the pawn on b2.} 
9. Qc1 {A logical move, trying to solve both problems at once, but it slows down White's ideas regarding their development. In earlier games, Black went for the active9...Nd4, but our choice is stronger.} 
9. Nf6 {A simple developing move.} 
10. Bxc6 {We shouldn't fear the weakening of our pawnstructure, as White's pieces aren't able to take advantage of the weakened queenside. In fact, White's light-squared will be seriously missed now.} 
10. bxc6
11. O-O
11. Bd6 {Threatening mate and White can't stop the threat by playing Bf4.} 
12. g3
12. Ng4 {Hitting the bishop on e3 as well as preparing ...Qh5.} 
13. Bf4
13. Qh5 {Renewing the mating threat.} 
14. h4
14. Bc5 {Avoiding the exchange of bishops and enabling the queen to come to f4, while the rook on f1 can't move any longer as that drops the pawn on f2.} 
15. Nc3 {Hoping to get the knight to e4.} 
15. Rhe8 {Preventing White's plan and now both the open files are under Black's control. White's major pieces are unable to join the game. Apart from the tactical possibilities against the pawn on f2, Black has the simple plan of playing ...f7-f6 and ...g7-g5. Black is just completely winning.} 
