9. Nf6 {An important developing move, as Black connects the rooks. Although White enjoys the bishop pair, I don't see a good plan employing these long-range monsters yet. Black's venturing some active play against White's pawns on c3 and d4 and therefore isn't intending to release the tension anytime soon with ....e5-e4 (unless it would win material of course).} 
10. c4 {Understandably White would like to expand in the centre in order to take away the pressure against these pawns.} 
10. Qe4 {This adventurous move is the way to go. Note that White isn't able to trap the queen with Bd3 as Black still has the escape of taking on f3 and move the queen to h4.} 
11. d5 {By advancing the pawn to d5, White prepares to win the knight on c6 with the clever Bd3, which attacks the queen and unpins their own d-pawn so that the knight can safely be taken.} 
11. Bxf3 {Forced, but strong. White can't take back with the bishop as that leaves the pawn on c4 undefended.} 
12. gxf3
12. Qh4 {Finally the queen has found a safe place. The position is very unbalanced and that's exactly what Black was looking for. From a practical perspective I believe Black's position is easier to handle as White's king is exposed and knights are usually tricky pieces.} 
