12. Ne7 {The simplest reaction. Given the chance, Black will trade off the knight for bishop on e2 and guide the other knight to d4. By the way, White's original plan of playing a2-a4 isn't dangerous, because after axb5 Black still has ...Qxa1 followed by a fork on c2.12...Qg6?this is far less effective now, as White will simply ignore the threat by playing13.Nxb5!in order to justify the last move, Black has to continue playing in a principled manner with13...Nc2+?14.Kf1Nxa1Black is a full rook up.15.Nxa7+Kb816.Qa4+-But the position is deadly lost.} 
13. Nxb5
13. Nxe2 {Eliminating that dangerous bishop.} 
14. Qxe2
14. Kb8 {Overprotecting the pawn on a7 and thus freeing the queen, which likely goes to e6. Black has a good game.} 
