[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. Nf3
3. Bg4
4. Be2
4. Nc6
5. d4 {The most ambitious and frequently played move. White is aiming to get in a quick c2-c4 and d4-d5, questioning the knight on c6. At the same time, the pawn on d4 offers Black counterplay in the centre and naturally play is becoming quite sharp in this line.} 
5. O-O-O {The tension in the centre increases every move! By castling queenside the black king has found a safe place, while the rook exerts pressure against the pawn on d4.} 
6. Be3 {White protects the pawn on d4 one more time.} 
6. e5 {We are fighting back in the centre, undermining the pawn on d4 as well as getting ready to bring our dark-squared bishop out to b4 at the right moment.} 
7. c4
7. Qa5+ {Moving the queen away from the threat with a check. White has to be careful that the centre doesn't collapse straightaway.} 
8. Bd2 {The only sensible way of dealing with the check as otherwise the pawn on d4 will be lost.} 
8. Qa6 {I believe this continuation sets more practical problems for White.} 
9. c5 {The most challenging continuation, as White attacks the queen on a6.} 
9. Bxf3 {A very precise intermediate move to weaken the kingside structure. White can't take the queen on a6 as Black takes on d1 and will remain a piece up.} 
10. gxf3 {White has to recapture in this way, so that the black queen remains under threat.} 
10. b5 {The only move to save the queen. At first this move looks quite bizarre, but the good news is that the centre will be opened. Various moves have been tried here by White, but Black seems to be doing alright after all of them.} 
11. d5 {A provocation to let Black capture the pawn on d5 with the rook, but we are not falling for that idea!} 
11. Nd4 {The knight is excellently placed on e4 where it counts on the support of the pawn on e5. White's pawns on c5 and d5 are hanging, so White got to act immediately.11...Rxd5?Black isn't advised to take with the rook on d5, as White gains valuable time attacking it.12.Nc3Rxc513.b4!another impressive punch!13...Nxb414.Rb1the open b-file turns out to be very problematic for Black14...Nc615.Nxb5↑White has a massive initiative.} 
12. Nc3 {White protects the pawn on d5 and hopes to generate some pressure against the pawn on b5.} 
12. Bxc5 {A juicy pawn!} 
13. a4
13. Qg6 {The typical idea for this particular line. White can't castle, while ...Nc2 is also a threat.} 
14. Ne4 {Prevents the fork on c2 and attacks the bishop on c5.} 
14. Rxd5 {Another valuable pawn, while defending the bishop at the same time.} 
15. axb5
15. Bb6 {Securing the queenside. White is now totally lost in Stankovic-Cabarkapa, Paracin 2022.} 
