6. c4 {Frankly, the main point of refraining from an early Nc3 is to be able to play this move and gain more influence in the centre.} 
6. Qf5 {The best square for the queen, keeping the d-file free for the rook on d8, while White isn't able to keep harassing the queen. With the last move, Black is intending to take on f3 after which the pawn on d4 is hanging.} 
7. Be3 {The main move. By developing the bishop to e3 White believes the pawn on d4 to be well supported. However, for unprepared players Black's next two moves may come as a huge shock!} 
7. Bxf3 {The most straightforward approach as Black is planning to win the pawn on d4.Alternatives like7...e5and7...Nf6are playable but aren't ensuring Black full equality.} 
8. Bxf3
8. Nxd4 {The tactical justification!} 
9. Bg4 {Doesn't win the queen, as Black still has} 
9. Nc2+ {Deflecting the queen from the protection of the bishop on g4.} 
10. Qxc2
10. Qxg4 {Black is a pawn up, but there is no time to rest on our laurels yet.} 
11. O-O
11. a6 {A simple move which saves the a-pawn. True, it slightly weakens the queenside, but there is no reason to be afraid of White's attacking chances. Basically, there are two plans for White to prove compensation:  1) b2-b4-b5 or 2) c4-c5-c6.} 
12. b4 {Initiating an initiative against the black king.} 
12. Nh6 {The most precise continuation. The knight is on the way to f5 from where it controls a big number of squares and retains the option of trading off White's bishop on e3. Note that White isn't interested in taking on h6 as that opens the g-file for the rook, while the bishop may develop via the long diagonal.} 
13. Nd2
13. Qg6 {A good square for the queen from where it covers the 6th rank.} 
14. Qa4
14. e5 {Enabling the bishop to get developed.} 
15. b5
15. Be7 {Connecting the rooks. Black's edge is beyond any doubt.} 
