11. O-O {It is also possible to start with11.Qa4which after11...Qxd412.O-Otransposes to our Main Line.} 
11. Qxd4
12. Qa4 {Avoiding the exchange of queens and preparing some pressure against the a7-pawn.} 
12. e6 {It's actually very important to put the pawn on e6 and not on e5, to avoid an unpleasant bishop check on g4.} 
13. Nc3 {We have reached probably the most important tabiya of the 3.Nf3 system. Black is a pawn up, and if we manage to consolidate our position we will be faring well.   However, White has a lead in development and may quickly seize the initiative by attacking the black queen and/or targeting Black's queenside.} 
13. a6 {I am delighted to introduce a very important novelty here! Black no longer has to be concerned of ideas directly related to Nb5 and the pawn on a7. The ensuing lines are potentially incredibly sharp, but definitely worth giving a try.} 
14. Rad1
14. Qe5 {The only move, thanks to our previous move the queen no longer has to guard the queenside and instead will look for active play against the white king. If Black does get a chance to play ...Bd6 and ...Nf6 the position consolidates and we will be just a healthy pawn up.14...Qc5??15.b4!Qxb416.Rxd8+Kxd817.Rd1+and Black is lost in all the lines:17...Kc818.Qe8#is mate, while both17...Ke718.Qxb4+and17...Bd618.Qxb4(bishop is pinned) are losing the queen.} 
15. c5 {White is about to open the queenside with either ...c5-c6 or sacrificing its bishop on a6.} 
15. Bxc5 {Once again, the only move but life is great when you develop a piece grab a pawn at the same time!} 
16. Bxa6 {Obviously can't take the bishop now because of mate, but} 
16. Bd6 {The key intermediate move which sets up the mating threat on h2 and closes the d-file.} 
17. g3
17. bxa6
18. Qxa6+
18. Kd7 {The black king is absolutely safe.} 
