1. e4
1. d5
2. exd5
2. Qxd5
3. d3 {Recommended by Plichta, but frankly I had never seen this move before. I guess that's a good sign :) However, White's move isn't doing that bad, just a bit passive as the light-squared bishop can't be developed to the usual active square c4.} 
3. Nc6 {Reinforcing control over the d4-square is a typical strategy in most of the lines in the Scandinavian in which White refrains from occupying the square with a pawn. Also in this case the move makes a lot of sense.} 
4. Nc3
4. Qd8 {I guess dropping back with the queen is the easiest way of playing, maintaining a grip on the d4-square.} 
5. Nf3
5. e5 {Let's occupy the centre if White refrains from doing so.} 
6. Be2 {The alternative way to develop the bishop.} 
6. Nge7 {Preparing ...g7-g6, ... Bg7 and castling.} 
7. O-O
7. g6 {If Black does get the chance to place the bishop on g7 its position is a bit better, White's bishop on e2 isn't doing much and prevents the rook from exerting pressure against the pawn on e5.} 
8. d4 {A temporary pawn sacrifice in order to break free.} 
8. exd4
9. Nb5 {White tries to regain the pawn on d4.} 
9. Bg7
10. Bf4 {Hitting the pawn on c7.} 
10. Nd5 {Protecting the pawn and attacking the bishop on f4.} 
11. Bg5 {Trying to provoke ...f7-f6 when the bishop on g7 no longer protects the pawn on d4.} 
11. Nce7 {Simple and effective.} 
12. Nbxd4
12. h6 {By questioning the bishop, White faces a dilemma. Giving up the pair of bishops is not desirable, but retreating to h4 relinquishes control over the f4-square, which the black knight can occupy.} 
13. Bb5+ {White is planning to meet13...c6with14.Nxc6. No need to enter these complications.} 
13. Bd7
14. Bxe7
14. Nxe7
15. Bxd7+
15. Qxd7 {With a very comfortable, perhaps even slightly better position for Black thanks to the beautiful bishop exerting pressure along the a1-h8 diagonal.} 
