2. Nf3 {The Tennison Gambit, named after the Danish amateur player Otto Mandrup Tennison. This is a typical pre-move for online games. It's almost never seen in OTB games as it's pretty bad for White actually.} 
2. dxe4 {We happily capture the pawn and threaten the knight on f3.} 
3. Ng5 {The only way to justify White's previous move. White is about to regain the pawn on e4.In a way this motif resembles The Budapest Gambit (1.d4Nf62.c4e53.dxe5Ng4) in which Black aims to regains the pawn on e5.} 
3. Bf5 {The principled move, as Black sticks to the valuable pawn on e4 and brings out the light-squared bishop before placing the pawn on e6.} 
4. Nc3 {Planning to recapture the pawn on e4.} 
4. Nf6 {Simple and effective development. White has a hard time regaining the pawn.} 
5. Bc4 {Targetting the pawn on f7.} 
5. e6
6. f3 {The mostly played move. White makes a real pawn sacrifice of it.} 
6. Nbd7 {A clever insertion, as White isn't able to win the pawn back. I like this continuation even better than taking on f3 straightaway, which is also possible.} 
7. fxe4
7. Nxe4 {The point!} 
8. Ncxe4
8. Bxe4
9. Nxe4
9. Qh4+ {Black will regain the piece.} 
10. Nf2
10. Qxc4 {White has no compensation whatsoever.} 
