[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. d3 {A very modest move. Whenever this move is played against other openings White is usually aiming for a sort of King's Indian setup with Nbd2, g3, Bg2, Nf3 etc.} 
2. dxe4 {The principled reaction.} 
3. dxe4
3. Qxd1+
4. Kxd1 {White's king will be stuck in the centre, but since queens have been exchanged it's not something White has to be worried about.} 
4. Nc6 {Aiming for quick development on the queenside. I'd rather refrain from an early ...e7-e5 which gives the game too much a static character and doesn't offer Black any serious chances playing for an advantage. Instead, I'd like to propose an alternative and more ambitious plan based on ...f7-f5.} 
5. Be3
5. f5 {Now, taking on f5 leads to similar play we get to see in the line with5.c3f56.exf5, but instead let's examine what happens if White tries to support the pawn on e4.} 
6. Nd2
6. Nf6
7. f3 {This move doesn't offer White any stability in the centre.} 
7. fxe4 {White doesn't want to recapture with the f-pawn as that allows Black to put the knight on g4 and exchange White's dark-squared bishop.} 
8. Nxe4
8. Bf5 {If White takes on f6 Black takes back with the e-pawn, when the two open files offer plenty of active play against the white king.} 
9. Bd3
9. O-O-O {Since the bishop on d3 is pinned, Black actually threatens to win a pawn by taking on e4.} 
10. Ke2
10. Nb4 {Intending to take the bishop and weaken White's pawn structure. Black has a pleasant initiative.} 
