1. e4
1. d5
2. d4 {Rather than taking the pawn, White decides to sacrifice it!} 
2. dxe4 {The principled reaction.} 
3. Nc3 {The most common reaction. White intends to recapture the pawn with the knight.} 
3. Nf6 {Simply defending the pawn. By the way, this variation could also be reached via the 1.d4 move order, so if you were in doubt this course is just much more than a complete repertoire against 1.e4 :)} 
4. Bg5 {The second most popular move, but one we can easily deal with.} 
4. Bf5 {We stick to the pawn on e4, as long as possible.} 
5. Bxf6 {Doubling the pawns isn't really a weakening of Black's pawn formation, and certainly not worth giving up the bishop pair that easily.} 
5. exf6 {Capturing away from the centre to accelerate our development.} 
6. Qe2 {The consistent follow-up as White still plans on regaining the pawn on e4 and in the meantime prepares to castle queenside. Moreover, we have to reckon with Qb5 ideas, so the following response seems adequate.} 
6. Nc6 {Eyeing the pawn on d4.} 
7. O-O-O {Inviting Black taking on d4 which we rather decline for obvious reasons.} 
7. Be7
8. Nxe4
8. O-O {Black is very comfortable, having completed its development already by move 8. White still needs to make a couple of moves to accomplish that task, which proves the misplacement of the queen on e2.} 
9. g4
9. Bc8 {A fantastic idea. The bishop goes back to its initial square to keep an eye on the pawn on g4, so that White can't develop its knight to f3. Probably next is ...f6-f5 in order to undouble the f-pawns. Black has a significant advantage.} 
