[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. d4 {Rather than taking the pawn, White decides to sacrifice it!} 
2. dxe4 {The principled reaction.} 
3. Nc3 {The most common reaction. White intends to recapture the pawn with the knight.} 
3. Nf6 {Simply defending the pawn. By the way, this variation could also be reached via the 1.d4 move order, so if you were in doubt this course is just much more than a complete repertoire against 1.e4 :)} 
4. f3 {Welcome to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, a popular variation at club level.} 
4. exf3 {Let's once again accept the challenge by simply capturing the pawn!} 
5. Nxf3 {The most logical way to recapture on f3.} 
5. c6 {From all Black's options I like this one the best. It's a sort of useful waiting move to see how White is going to develop the light-squared bishop. And of course, it also actually fits well with structures normally arising from the Scandinavian.} 
6. Bc4 {This is by far White's most popular move, as it looks at the vulnerable f7-pawn and thereby creates several tactical ideas. However, with precise play Black is able to prove White's move to be inaccurate.} 
6. Bf5 {Next is ...e7-e6.} 
7. O-O
7. e6 {In the case of8.Ne5?!we will get a transposition to the line with 7.Ne5.} 
8. Bg5 {White proceeds developing in a normal way, then the ideal setup for Black is just with ...Be7 and Nbd7} 
8. Be7
9. Qe2
9. O-O
10. Rad1
10. Nbd7 {White has optimized its position, but what to do next? The bishop isn't doing well on c4, biting granite on e6 and therefore I think Black can be satisfied with its extra pawn.} 
