2. d4 {Rather than taking the pawn, White decides to sacrifice it!} 
2. dxe4 {The principled reaction.} 
3. Nc3 {The most common reaction. White intends to recapture the pawn with the knight.} 
3. Nf6 {Simply defending the pawn. By the way, this variation could also be reached via the 1.d4 move order, so if you were in doubt this course is just much more than a complete repertoire against 1.e4 :)} 
4. f3 {Welcome to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, a popular variation at club level.} 
4. exf3 {Let's once again accept the challenge by simply capturing the pawn!} 
5. Nxf3 {The most logical way to recapture on f3.} 
5. c6 {From all Black's options I like this one the best. It's a sort of useful waiting move to see how White is going to develop the light-squared bishop. And of course, it also actually fits well with structures normally arising from the Scandinavian.} 
6. Bd3 {Probably White's best option, not giving Black a chance to bring the bishop out to f5.} 
6. Bg4 {But then we are going one square further!} 
7. Be3 {Protecting the pawn on d4, preparing to castle.} 
7. e6
8. O-O
8. Nbd7
9. Qe1 {White's attacking setup starts taking shape, but there is no reason to panick!} 
9. Be7 {Discouraging the queen from coming over to h4 and keeping the knight on f6 well supported.} 
10. Ne5
10. O-O {Black keeps its pieces well-defended. At first, the idea of castling kingside may seem as if it just plays into White's hand, but in the following variations, I will prove White's attack isn't dangerous at all.} 
11. Qg3 {Threatening the bishop.} 
11. Bh5 {On its way to g6.} 
12. Qh3
12. Bg6
13. Nxg6
13. hxg6 {In general Black should be content with the outcome of the opening. White's only hope for compensation is to launch a blitz attack via the h-file.} 
14. Rf4
14. e5 {An attack on the wing should be met by a strike in the center!} 
15. Rh4 {Threatening mate.} 
15. Nh5 {Closing the h-file and attacking the rook on h4.} 
16. Rxh5 {No other option.} 
16. gxh5
17. Qxh5 {Threatening mate on h7 this time.} 
17. Nf6 {The second knight reaches f6 to cover the mating threat.} 
18. Qh4
18. exd4 {Aiming further simplifications.} 
19. Bxd4 {With the idea of eliminating Black's most important defender.} 
19. Nh5 {Attacking the queen.} 
20. Qxh5
20. Qxd4+ {Check!} 
21. Kh1
21. Qh4 {The mating threat has been covered. Black is a full exchange up and shouldn't have any problems converting.} 
