1. e4
1. d5
2. e5 {This move has seldomly been seen at high level. By advancing the pawn on e5, White is grabbing space in the centre. However, in most lines we will see that it likely more becomes a weakness rather than an asset.} 
2. c5 {Black anticipates that White is going to support the pawn on e5 by creating a chain with c3-d4.} 
3. Nf3 {This logical move is imprecise as it offers Black an additional possibility.} 
3. Bg4 {By pinning the knight we indirectly increase the pressure against the pawn on e5.} 
4. Be2
4. Nc6 {The pawn on e5 is already in big trouble. Black is threatening to take on f3 and e5.} 
5. c4 {Trying to repair the damage of a botched opening experiment.} 
5. e6 {Keep it simple.} 
6. cxd5
6. Qxd5 {White has a horrible pawnstructure.} 
7. Nc3
7. Qd7 {The queen is doing well on d7. Apart from the vulnerable pawn on e5, White now also has to deal with a backward pawn on d2.} 
8. Qa4 {Hitting the bishop on g4.} 
8. Bxf3
9. Bxf3 {Now taking on e5 allows White to trade queens and take on b7.} 
9. Nge7 {To be able recapturing with a piece on c6 in case White decides giving up its bishop.} 
10. O-O
10. O-O-O {Followed by ...Kb8 (protecting the pawn on a7) after which the knight on c6 is free to move.} 
