3. Bf5 {The most precise continuation. Black would like to play ...e7-e6 but first the light-squared bishop needs to be activated before it gets stuck within its own pawn formation.} 
4. d4
4. e6 {Simple and strong. Black obtains a favorable version of the Advanced Variation of two popular openings.  1) French: after1.e4e62.d4d53.e5c54.c3Black's light-squared remains passive on c8. In our line, it's outside the pawn chain controlling various valuable squares.  2) Caro-Kann: after1.e4c62.d4d53.e5Bf5Black spends an extra tempo by playing twice with the c-pawn. Let's see how we can try to take advantage of this small plus!} 
5. Nf3 {The most common move, as the knight supports the chain by overprotecting the pawns on d4 and e5.} 
5. Nc6 {Dito: the knight puts pressure on White's pawns.} 
6. Bd3 {A typical move you would often seen at club level. Trading off these bishops seems to enlighten the pressure, but what matters is what remains on the board. The bishop on c1 is worse than their counterpart on f8.} 
6. Bxd3
7. Qxd3
7. Rc8 {Ready to open the c-file.} 
8. O-O
8. cxd4
9. cxd4
9. Nb4 {Attacking the queen and to trap the rook in the corner.} 
10. Qb5+
10. Qd7
11. Qxd7+
11. Kxd7 {The king is actually well placed on d7, supporting the rook on c8.} 
12. Nc3 {Closing the file.} 
12. Ne7 {This is not just a boring queenless middlegame. Black has an edge! Why?   Well, as mentioned black has the better bishop and White has to take care of the weak pawn on d4, the base of the chain, which could easily come under the attack of the black knights. Another important plan is challenging the head of the chain, White's pawn on e5, with ...f7-f6 when after ...exf6, ...gxf6 Black obtains a mobile pawn centre which eventually may turn into a passed pawn.} 
