[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Second Move Alternatives "]
[Black "2.Nc3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. d5
2. Nc3 {A popular move among club players who don't fancy a theoretical battle in the Scandinavian. White develops a piece, protects the pawn on e4 and offers the possible transposition into a French (2...e6) or Caro-Kann (2...c6).} 
2. d4 {The principled reaction. Black releases the central tension, grabs space in the centre and forces White to waste some more time finding a suitable square for the knight (and other pieces!).2...dxe43.Nxe4there is the possibility of playing3...Qd5!?and now after4.Nc3we are back at familiar Scandinavian territory. You can choose for yourself which option you like the best, but given the chance I prefer to take the opportunity to play for an advantage by move 2!} 
3. Nce2
3. e5 {The most natural move, giving Black plenty of developing options.} 
4. Ng3 {The main point of White's opening choice. The knight has been transferred to the kingside and frees the path for the light-squared bishop.} 
4. Be6 {The most precise move, preventing White from getting its bishop to c4. Of course, White can play moves like d3, Be2, Nf3 and so on, but at some point, there are no more useful moves and the lack of space will pay its toll.   Hence, in subsequent play, we will mainly try to anticipate White's main plan of getting the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 
5. Bb5+
5. c6 {As you see, it's clever not to play ...c7-c5 too fast in order to meet the bishop check with this move.} 
6. Ba4 {Ideally, White would now trade off the light-squared bishops and play d2-d3 followed by f2-f4 with quite some nice practical play on the kingside, but it's Black's turn first!} 
6. Na6 {Heading for the c5-square.} 
7. c3 {is met by} 
7. Nc5
8. Bb3
8. Nxb3
9. axb3
9. d3 {White is in a complete bind, as we might witness in other scenarios as well. The pawn on d3 can't be challenged.} 
