2. e4
2. d4 {The principled reaction. Black releases the central tension, grabs space in the centre and forces White to waste some more time finding a suitable square for the knight (and other pieces!).} 
3. Nce2
3. e5 {The most natural move, giving Black plenty of developing options.} 
4. Ng3 {The main point of White's opening choice. The knight has been transferred to the kingside and frees the path for the light-squared bishop.} 
4. Be6 {The most precise move, preventing White from getting its bishop to c4. Of course, White can simply play moves like d3, Be2, Nf3 and so on, but at some point there are no more useful moves and the lack of space will pay its toll. Hence, in subsequent play we will mainly try to anticipate White's main plan of getting the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 
5. c3 {A seemingly natural move, undermining the head of Black's pawn chain, but its drawbacks are shown soon.} 
5. Nc6 {Other moves to support the center have been tried in this position as well, but I favor this option, despite allowing White to make the subsequent move. If cxd4 occurs, Black has the opportunity to place a piece on d4 instead of recapturing with a pawn.5...d3?can't be recommended yet, because of6.Qf3!and next the d-pawn will be taken.} 
6. Bb5
6. Nge7 {Not allowing the doubling of the queenside pawns.} 
7. Nf3 {Intending Nxe5.} 
7. a6 {Questioning the bishop is the point of Black's previous move.} 
8. Ba4 {8.Bxc6+Nxc6∓gives Black a very easy game.} 
8. d3 {Locking the up bishop on c1 at the expense of the e-pawn.} 
9. Ng5 {Trying to force the bishop to leave the a2-g8 diagonal when Bb3, attacking the pawn on f7, would be unpleasant.9.Nxe5b5is another line discussed in Chapter 16.} 
9. Ng6 {Very concrete play as Black threatens to capture the knight and aims for quick development, not minding the trade on e6.} 
10. Nxe6
10. fxe6 {Black is about to play ...Bc5 and ...O-O when the pressure along the f-file is hard to withstand. Note that White is unable to undermine the pawn on d3.} 
